James Capasso || {{flagicon|USA}} || November 2015 || March 2016 || Contract end\n|-\n| Sascha Gergele || {{flagicon|GER}} || April 2016 || March 2018 || Contract end\n|-\n| Robin Kaltenbach || {{flagicon|GER}} || April 2018 || ||\n|}\n\n== Notable players and coaches ==\n\n=== Notable players ===\n\n==== Current players ====\n\n==== Former players ====\n* Serdar Antac ({{flagicon|TUR}}, 2013 - 2015): German champion 2003, [[Willi Brinkmann Cup]] winner 2001, Turkish champion 2006, 2007, 2008 and 2009, [[IWBF Champions Cup]] winner 2008 and 2009, [[Kitakyushu Champions Cup]] winner 2008 and 2009, [[European Wheelchair Basketball Championship|European champion]] (Group B) with Turkey 2006\n* Janic Binda ({{flagicon|SWI}}, 2014 - 2016): Swiss champion 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013 and 2014, Swiss cup winner 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013 and 2014, Swiss international\n* Paul James Capasso ({{flagicon|USA}}, 2014 - 2016): US champion 1993, 1995 and 2004, [[Andr\u00e9 Vergauwen Cup]] winner 2014, US international\n* Nico Dreim\u00fcller ({{flagicon|GER}}, 2010 - 2013): German champion 2015 and 2017, German cup winner 2015, 2017 and 2018, Champions cup winner 2015, German international\n* Pieter Dries ({{flagicon|BEL}}, 2013 - 2015): [[European Wheelchair Basketball Championship|European champion]] (Group B) with Belgium 2008, Belgian cup winner 2016\n* Sascha Gergele ({{flagicon|GER}}, 2009 - 2019): German champion 2003, Willi Brinkmann Cup winner 2001, German international\n* Philipp H\u00e4feli ({{flagicon|SWI}}, 2014 - 2015): Swiss champion 2010, 2011 and 2012, Swiss cup winner 2010, 2011 and 2012, German champion 2017, German cup winner 2017 and 2018, Swiss international\n* Matthias Heimbach ({{flagicon|GER}}, 2013 - 2016): German cup winner 2008, German champion 2009, IWBF Champions cup finalist 2010, European championship finalist with Germany 2011, German international\n* Kai M\u00f6ller ({{flagicon|GER}}, 2015 - 2016): Italian champion 2013, Italian cup winner 2013, German cup winner 2018, German international\n* Sebastian Spitznagel ({{flagicon|GER}}, 2010 - 2014): German champion 2003, German international\n* Klaus Weber ({{flagicon|GER}}, 2009 - 2013): German champion 1994 and 2003, German cup winner 1993, Willi Brinkmann Cup winner 2001, German international\n* Jacob Michael Williams ({{flagicon|USA}}, 2015 - 2016): US champion 2015, German champion 2018, 2019 and 2020, German cup winner 2019, Champions Cup winner 2018, US international\n\n=== Notable coaches ===\n* Christa Weber ({{flagicon|GER}}, 2009 - 2013): German champion 1994, 1997 and 2003, German cup winner 1993, Willi Brinkmann Cup winner 2001, Coach of German women's national team, Coach of German women's under-19 national team\n* Clifford Fisher ({{flagicon|USA}}, 2014 - 2015): Italian champion 2004, 2009 and 2010, Italian cup winner 2004, 2007 and 2010, Italian supercup winner 2008, Turkish champion 2011, [[Andr\u00e9 Vergauwen Cup]] winner 2004, Willy Brinkmann Cup winner 2008, European champion with Italy 2003 and 2005, Coach of Italian national team, Coach of Italian national under-22 team, Coach of Belgian national team\n* Paul James Capasso ({{flagicon|USA}}, 2015 - 2016): [[Andr\u00e9 Vergauwen Cup]] winner 2014\n\n== Miscellaneous ==\n\n===Naming===\nThe naming in wheel chair basketball at 1.FC Kaiserslautern is influenced by the club's image from soccer: The team name ''Rolling Devils'' traces back to the nickname ''Red Devils'' of 1.FC Kaiserslautern's soccer team, the wheel chair basketball team like the club's professional soccer team also has a [[devil]] at [[mascot]], and like the [[Fritz-Walter-Stadion]] in soccer, the home playing site of FCK Rolling Devils is commonly known as ''hell (of Kaiserslautern)''.<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/FCKRollingDevils/photos/pb.169800396366053.-2207520000.1416942502./772454112767342 H\u00f6llisch scharf: die Rolling Devils (Hellish hot: the Rolling Devils) ''Rollt.'', edition 1/2014] (accessed on November 25, 2014)</ref>\n\n===Fans===\n[[File:Fanchoreografie 2014.jpg|thumb|Supporters' choreography for the championship 2014]]\nFrom 2012 to 2016, FCK Rolling Devils welcomed on average more than 250 spectators at their home games and were thereby one of the most visited wheel chair basketball teams in Germany. Devils [[Sports fan#Sports|fan]] culture has strong ties to [[1.FC Kaiserslautern#Club culture|1.FC Kaiserslautern's club culture in soccer]]: the unofficial [[Sports fan#Sports|fan club]] ''Rolling Devils Supporters'' overlaps with soccer fan clubs and the fan culture features many [[Ultras|elements from soccer fandom]].<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?v=753094508036636 Kaiserslautern's Red Wall (Kaiserslauterns Rote Wand), Rolling Devils Facebook-Video] (accessed on April 9, 2014)</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3UXaV6cryTk (23.03.14 - Teil 1/8) Rolling Devils 1.FC KAISERSLAUTERN - RSV Lahn-Dill II, Youtube-Video] (accessed on April 9, 2014)</ref>\n\n===Media===\nFCK Rolling Devils host a [[homepage]],<ref>[http://www.rollingdevils.de Rolling Devils Homepage] (accessed on November 25, 2014)</ref> one of the most popular [[Facebook]] sites in German wheel chair basketball<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/FCKRollingDevils Rolling Devils Facebook site] (accessed on November 25, 2014)</ref> and from 2014 to 2016 also their own [[YouTube]] channel.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC5ad1S6cbRcXomyxlcyr9SA FCK Rolling Devils YouTube channel] (accessed on November 25, 2014)</ref>\n\n===Awards===\nFor their social commitment, FCK Rolling Devils in 2011 received the Stern des Sports (''Star of Sports'') in bronze from the [[Deutscher Olympischer Sportbund|German Olympic Sports Confederation]]<ref>[http://www.sterne-des-sports.de/de/sterne-des-sports/ Deutscher Olympischer Sportbund - Sterne des Sports (German Olympic Sports Confederation - Stars of sports)] (accessed on November 25, 2014)</ref> and in 2013 the Br\u00fcckenpreis (''Bridge award'') of the federal state [[Rhineland-Palatinate]].<ref>[http://www.rlp.de/no_cache/aktuelles/presse/einzelansicht/archive/2013/december/article/malu-dreyer-dank-fuer-gute-ideen-und-grosses-engagement/ Verleihung des Br\u00fcckenpreises 2013 (Bridge awards 2013)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222143656/http://www.rlp.de/no_cache/aktuelles/presse/einzelansicht/archive/2013/december/article/malu-dreyer-dank-fuer-gute-ideen-und-grosses-engagement/ |date=2014-02-22 }} (accessed on November 25, 2014)</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.rollingdevils.de/ Official website]\n* [http://www.facebook.com/FCKRollingdevils Facebook site]\n\n[[Category:1. FC Kaiserslautern| ]]\n[[Category:Wheelchair basketball teams]]\n[[Category:Basketball teams in Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox basketball club\n| name            = FCK Rolling Devils\n| color1          = <!-- or | colour1 = -->\n| color2          = <!-- or | colour2 = -->\n| logo            =\n| nickname        = Rolling red devils\n| leagues         = Regional league (3rd division)\n| founded         = September 2009\n| dissolved       =\n| history         = \n| arena           = Sports Hall of Schillerschule Kaiserslautern\n| location        = [[Kaiserslautern]]<br />([[Rhineland-Palatinate]], [[Germany]])\n| colors          = Red/White/Black\n| current         = \n| sponsor         = \n| president       = Sascha Gergele\n| vice-presidents = Melanie J\u00f6rg\n| coach           = Robin Kaltenbach\n| ownership       = \n| championships   = Regional Cup Winner 2010<br />Regional League Champion 2011<br />2nd Federal League Champion 2014<br />Regional League Champion 2019\n| website         = [http://www.rollingdevils.de/ www.rollingdevils.de]\n| h_body          = C32A28\n| h_pattern_b     = \n| h_shorts        = C32A28\n| h_pattern_s     = \n| a_body          = 000000\n| a_pattern_b     = \n| a_shorts        = 000000\n| a_pattern_s     = \n}}\nThe '''FCK Rolling Devils''' are a [[Wheelchair basketball|wheelchair basketball club]] located in [[Kaiserslautern]] with [[Football in Germany|German soccer club]] [[1. FC Kaiserslautern]] acting as name sponsor. Their first team played in the [[Rollstuhlbasketball-Bundesliga]] from 2014 to 2016 and now plays in the third-class regional league.\n\n== History ==\nThe wheelchair basketball team of 1. FC Kaiserslautern was founded in September 2009 as a part of the club's [[Basketball|basketball department]]. The Rolling Devils entered league play of the German Wheelchair Sports Federation<ref>[http://www.drs.org German Wheelchair Sports Federation (Deutscher Rollstuhl-Sportverband) german homepage] (accessed on March 1, 2014)</ref> in the season 2010/11 on the level of the third-class Regional League (Central Conference). The team won the Regional Cup<ref>[http://www.drs-rollstuhlbasketball.de/index.php?id=43  German Wheelchair Sports Regional Cup (Regionspokal) winners] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224114315/http://www.drs-rollstuhlbasketball.de/index.php?id=43 |date=2013-12-24 }} (accessed on March 5, 2014)</ref> and advanced to the quarter finals of the German National Cup.<ref>[http://www2.drs-rollstuhlbasketball.de/ligen/showPokal.php?liga=drspokal German Wheelchair Sports Cup (DRS-Pokal) pairings]  (accessed on March 1, 2014)</ref> The Devils finished the season with the championship and promotion to the 2nd German Wheelchair Basketball Federal League (Southern Conference).<ref>[http://www2.drs-rbb.de/ligen/showOverview.php?liga=bl2s 2nd German Wheelchair Basketball Federal League (Southern Conference) (2. Rollstuhlbasketball-Bundesliga S\u00fcd) rankings] (accessed on March 1, 2015)</ref>\n\nIn the next two seasons the Devils dropped from German Wheelchair Sports Cup in the group stage, but finished as runners-up in the 2nd Federal League. In 2013 the team participated for the German Wheelchair Sports Federation in [[International Wheelchair Basketball Federation]] Euroleague 3 and finished in third place.<ref>[http://www.iwbf-europe.org/index.php/news/results/327-results-euroleague-3-2013 IWBF EuroLeague 3 results 2013] (accessed on March 1, 2014)</ref><ref>[http://www.iwbf-europe.org/index.php/eurocup/ranking-clubs IWBF Eurocup club rankings] (accessed on March 1, 2014)</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, FCK Rolling Devils re-established as a separate wheelchair basketball department.<ref>[http://fck.de/en/1-fc-kaiserslautern/fck/structure/departments.html 1.FC Kaiserslautern club departments] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129120412/http://fck.de/en/1-fc-kaiserslautern/fck/structure/departments.html |date=2014-11-29 }} (accessed on March 1, 2014)</ref> In the season 2013/14 the Rolling Devils again advanced to the quarter finals of the German National Cup and in the third attempt won the championship in the 2nd German Federal League thereby gaining promotion to the 1st German Federal League.<ref>[http://www2.drs-rbb.de/ligen/showOverview.php?liga=bl1 1st German Wheelchair Basketball Federal League 2014 (1. Rollstuhlbasketball-Bundesliga) rankings] (accessed on March 1, 2015)</ref> In the season 2014/15, the Devils made it again to the quarter finals of the German National Cup and finished their first season in the 1st German Federal League on rank 7 and thereby as the best promoted team of the last four seasons.\n\nIn July 2015, the spin-off of FCK Rolling Devils as independent club with 1.FC Kaiserslautern acting as name sponsor took place. The wheelchair basketball department at 1.FC Kaiserslautern was suspended at the annual general meeting of the club in December 2015. In the season 2015/16, the Devils again made it to the quarter finals of the German National Cup and finished the season on rank 7.\n\nIn August 2016, the club withdrew its first team from the 1st German Federal League for financial and sports reasons and continued league play with their second team in the third-class regional league. In the next two seasons, the Rolling Devils finished on rank 3. In the season 2018/19, the Devils won the championship and right for promotion to the 2nd German Wheelchair Basketball Federal League (Southern Conference), but decided to stay in the regional league for financial reasons. The season 2019/20 ended ahead of schedule because of the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]] and the Rolling Devils finished with several games less played than the other teams on rank 4.\n\n== Honors ==\n\n===National===\n* Regional Cup (Central Conference) Winner 2010\n* Regional League (Central Conference) Champion 2011 (''Regionalliga Mitte'', 3rd division)\n* 2nd Federal League (Southern Conference) Champion 2014\n* Regional League (Central Conference) Champion 2019 (''Regionalliga Mitte'', 3rd division)\n\n===2nd team===\n* First League (Central Conference) Champion 2014 (''Oberliga Mitte'', 4th division)\n* Regional Cup (Central Conference) Winner 2014\n\n== Players ==\n\n=== Roster 2020/21 ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|- style=\"background-color:#ABCDEF;\"\n! Number\n! Name\n! Nationality\n! Year of birth\n! [[Wheelchair basketball#Classifications|Classification]]\n! [[Basketball#Positions|Position]]\n! In the club since\n! Former club\n|}\n\n=== Leaves 2020 ===\n\n== Season by season ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|- style=\"background-color:#ABCDEF;\"\n! Season\n! League\n! Position (Teams)\n! W\n! D\n! L\n! Points\n! Baskets\n! National cup competitions\n! International competitions\n|- style=\"background-color:#B9FFC5;\"\n| 2010/11 || Regional league (Central conference) || 1 (8) || 14 || 0 || 0 || 28:0 || 1228:428 || Regional Cup: Winner<br />German Cup: quarter finals ||\n|-\n| 2011/12 || 2nd Federal League (Southern conference) || 2 (8) || 11 || 0 || 3 || 22:6 || 961:767 || German Cup: group stage ||\n|-\n| 2012/13 || 2nd Federal League (Southern conference) || 2 (8) || 10 || 0 || 4 || 20:8 || 908:764 || German Cup: group 