national\n* Pieter Dries ({{flagicon|BEL}}, 2013 - 2015): [[European Wheelchair Basketball Championship|European champion]] (Group B) with Belgium 2008, Belgian cup winner 2016\n* Sascha Gergele ({{flagicon|GER}}, 2009 - 2019): German champion 2003, Willi Brinkmann Cup winner 2001, German international\n* Philipp H\u00e4feli ({{flagicon|SWI}}, 2014 - 2015): Swiss champion 2010, 2011 and 2012, Swiss cup winner 2010, 2011 and 2012, German champion 2017, German cup winner 2017 and 2018, Swiss international\n* Matthias Heimbach ({{flagicon|GER}}, 2013 - 2016): German cup winner 2008, German champion 2009, IWBF Champions cup finalist 2010, European championship finalist with Germany 2011, German international\n* Kai M\u00f6ller ({{flagicon|GER}}, 2015 - 2016): Italian champion 2013, Italian cup winner 2013, German cup winner 2018, German international\n* Sebastian Spitznagel ({{flagicon|GER}}, 2010 - 2014): German champion 2003, German international\n* Klaus Weber ({{flagicon|GER}}, 2009 - 2013): German champion 1994 and 2003, German cup winner 1993, Willi Brinkmann Cup winner 2001, German international\n* Jacob Michael Williams ({{flagicon|USA}}, 2015 - 2016): US champion 2015, German champion 2018, 2019 and 2020, German cup winner 2019, Champions Cup winner 2018, US international\n\n=== Notable coaches ===\n* Christa Weber ({{flagicon|GER}}, 2009 - 2013): German champion 1994, 1997 and 2003, German cup winner 1993, Willi Brinkmann Cup winner 2001, Coach of German women's national team, Coach of German women's under-19 national team\n* Clifford Fisher ({{flagicon|USA}}, 2014 - 2015): Italian champion 2004, 2009 and 2010, Italian cup winner 2004, 2007 and 2010, Italian supercup winner 2008, Turkish champion 2011, [[Andr\u00e9 Vergauwen Cup]] winner 2004, Willy Brinkmann Cup winner 2008, European champion with Italy 2003 and 2005, Coach of Italian national team, Coach of Italian national under-22 team, Coach of Belgian national team\n* Paul James Capasso ({{flagicon|USA}}, 2015 - 2016): [[Andr\u00e9 Vergauwen Cup]] winner 2014\n\n== Miscellaneous ==\n\n===Naming===\nThe naming in wheel chair basketball at 1.FC Kaiserslautern is influenced by the club's image from soccer: The team name ''Rolling Devils'' traces back to the nickname ''Red Devils'' of 1.FC Kaiserslautern's soccer team, the wheel chair basketball team like the club's professional soccer team also has a [[devil]] at [[mascot]], and like the [[Fritz-Walter-Stadion]] in soccer, the home playing site of FCK Rolling Devils is commonly known as ''hell (of Kaiserslautern)''.<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/FCKRollingDevils/photos/pb.169800396366053.-2207520000.1416942502./772454112767342 H\u00f6llisch scharf: die Rolling Devils (Hellish hot: the Rolling Devils) ''Rollt.'', edition 1/2014] (accessed on November 25, 2014)</ref>\n\n===Fans===\n[[File:Fanchoreografie 2014.jpg|thumb|Supporters' choreography for the championship 2014]]\nFrom 2012 to 2016, FCK Rolling Devils welcomed on average more than 250 spectators at their home games and were thereby one of the most visited wheel chair basketball teams in Germany. Devils [[Sports fan#Sports|fan]] culture has strong ties to [[1.FC Kaiserslautern#Club culture|1.FC Kaiserslautern's club culture in soccer]]: the unofficial [[Sports fan#Sports|fan club]] ''Rolling Devils Supporters'' overlaps with soccer fan clubs and the fan culture features many [[Ultras|elements from soccer fandom]].<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?v=753094508036636 Kaiserslautern's Red Wall (Kaiserslauterns Rote Wand), Rolling Devils Facebook-Video] (accessed on April 9, 2014)</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3UXaV6cryTk (23.03.14 - Teil 1/8) Rolling Devils 1.FC KAISERSLAUTERN - RSV Lahn-Dill II, Youtube-Video] (accessed on April 9, 2014)</ref>\n\n===Media===\nFCK Rolling Devils host a [[homepage]],<ref>[http://www.rollingdevils.de Rolling Devils Homepage] (accessed on November 25, 2014)</ref> one of the most popular [[Facebook]] sites in German wheel chair basketball<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/FCKRollingDevils Rolling Devils Facebook site] (accessed on November 25, 2014)</ref> and from 2014 to 2016 also their own [[YouTube]] channel.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC5ad1S6cbRcXomyxlcyr9SA FCK Rolling Devils YouTube channel] (accessed on November 25, 2014)</ref>\n\n===Awards===\nFor their social commitment, FCK Rolling Devils in 2011 received the Stern des Sports (''Star of Sports'') in bronze from the [[Deutscher Olympischer Sportbund|German Olympic Sports Confederation]]<ref>[http://www.sterne-des-sports.de/de/sterne-des-sports/ Deutscher Olympischer Sportbund - Sterne des Sports (German Olympic Sports Confederation - Stars of sports)] (accessed on November 25, 2014)</ref> and in 2013 the Br\u00fcckenpreis (''Bridge award'') of the federal state [[Rhineland-Palatinate]].<ref>[http://www.rlp.de/no_cache/aktuelles/presse/einzelansicht/archive/2013/december/article/malu-dreyer-dank-fuer-gute-ideen-und-grosses-engagement/ Verleihung des Br\u00fcckenpreises 2013 (Bridge awards 2013)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222143656/http://www.rlp.de/no_cache/aktuelles/presse/einzelansicht/archive/2013/december/article/malu-dreyer-dank-fuer-gute-ideen-und-grosses-engagement/ |date=2014-02-22 }} (accessed on November 25, 2014)</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.rollingdevils.de/ Official website]\n* [http://www.facebook.com/FCKRollingdevils Facebook site]\n\n[[Category:1. FC Kaiserslautern| ]]\n[[Category:Wheelchair basketball teams]]\n[[Category:Basketball teams in Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Alexander in KL", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update of club presidency", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FCK_Rolling_Devils"}
{"title_page": "Agnieszka Osiecka", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| name = Agnieszka Osiecka\n| image = File:Agnieszka Osiecka Polish writer.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Agnieszka Osiecka\n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1936|10|09}}\n| birth_place = [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]]\n| death_date = {{Death date|df=yes|1997|03|07}}\n| death_place = Warsaw, Poland\n| resting_place = [[Pow\u0105zki Cemetery]]\n| occupation = Poet, writer, author of theatre and television screenplays, film director and journalist\n| language = [[Polish language|Polish]]\n| nationality = Polish\n| period = \n| genre = \n| subject = \n| movement = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse = [[Wojciech Frykowski]] 1963-1964, Wojciech Jesionka 1966\n| children = [[Agata Passent]]\n| relatives = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = [[Cross_of_Merit_(Poland)|Cross of Merit]] 1979\n}}\n'''Agnieszka Osiecka''' (9 October 1936 \u2013 7 March 1997) was a [[poet]], [[writer]], author of theatre and television screenplays, film director and journalist. She was a prominent Polish songwriter, having authored the lyrics to more than 2000 songs, and is considered an icon of Polish culture.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/womensstudiesenc0001unse/page/1107|title=Women's studies encyclopedia|last=|first=|date=1999|publisher=Greenwood Press|others=Tierney, Helen.|year=|isbn=9780313310720|edition=Rev. and expanded|location=Westport, Conn.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/womensstudiesenc0001unse/page/1107 1107]|oclc=38504469}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nOsiecka was born in [[Warsaw]], the only child of Wiktor Osiecki, a pianist and composer of [[Serbs|Serbian]], [[Romanians|Romanian]]-[[Vlachs|Vlach]] and [[Hungarians|Hungarian]] descent, and a scholar Maria Sztechman. She spent her early years in [[Zakopane]] where her father played the piano at the Watra Restaurant. After World War II the Osiecki family moved to Warsaw and settled in the Saska K\u0119pa borough. The small flat soon became Osiecka\u2019s favourite place to work. She lived there almost her entire life. After her death, the ''Okularnicy'' Foundation placed a commemorative plaque on the building.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://culture.pl/en/artist/agnieszka-osiecka|title=Agnieszka Osiecka {{!}} Artist {{!}} Culture.pl|work=Culture.pl|access-date=2018-03-23|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAgnieszka was exceptionally gifted. She completed her coursework much more quickly than other students and graduated from Marie Curie-Sk\u0142odowska High School in 1952. She trained as a swimmer at Legia Sports Club and studied journalism at the [[University of Warsaw]] (1957\u201361) and film-directing at the prestigious [[National Film School in \u0141\u00f3d\u017a]] (1957\u201361) but dropped film-directing and started writing. Osiecka published essays and articles in the student press during her university years. She joined the famous [[Student Satirical Theatre]] (STS) in 1954 and wrote 166 political and lyrical songs for this company. She used to say \"I am a journalist, that is why some of my songs are reports which rhyme.\" She served on the artistic board of the STS Theatre until it closed in 1972.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Agnieszka Osiecka monument Warsaw 01.jpg|thumb|Agnieszka Osiecka monument in Warsaw]]\n1962 marked her debut on [[Polskie Radio|Polish National Radio]]. Renown Polish actress [[Kalina J\u0119drusik]] sang Osiecka's lyrics to a hit song by Franciszka Leszczy\u0144ska called \"My First Ball\" (''M\u00f3j pierwszy bal''). One year later at the first [[National Festival of Polish Song in Opole]] in 1963 Agnieszka achieved a major success winning the main prize and six other prizes for her lyrics: \"Piosenka o Okularnikach\u201c (music by Jaros\u0142aw Abram), as well as \"Bia\u0142e ma\u0142\u017ce\u0144stwo,\u201c \"Czerwony kapturek,\u201c \"Kochankowie z ulicy Kamiennej,\u201c \"Solo na kontrabasie\u201c and \"Ulice wielkich miast.\u201c<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.archiwumagnieszkiosieckiej.pl/dlibra/text?id=about-archive|title=dLibra Digital Library|last=Center|first=PSNC, Poznan Supercomputer and Networking|website=www.archiwumagnieszkiosieckiej.pl|language=en|access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n\nShe was now recognised as a prominent young poet and the Polish National Radio offered her a job to create and lead a team to broadcast ''The Radio Song Studio''. She also worked on theatre and television productions. Together with composer Adam S\u0142awi\u0144ski she wrote a series called \"Listy \u015bpiewaj\u0105ce\u201c (\"Singing Letters\u201c). Her first major theatre show \"Niech no tylko zakwitn\u0105 jab\u0142onie\u201c (\"Let the Apple-trees Bloom\") was staged at the [[Ateneum Theatre]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|year=1985|title=Theatre in Poland 1984|url=|journal=London Theatre Record|publisher=I. Herbert|volume=5|issue=1-13|pages=s.589|via=}}</ref>\n\nHer lyrics were set to music by such composers as [[Krzysztof Komeda]], [[Seweryn Krajewski]], [[Adam S\u0142awi\u0144ski]], [[Zygmunt Konieczny]], and others.\n\n==Personal life==\nOsiecka and her partner, the prominent journalist [[Daniel Passent]], had their only child, a daughter, [[Agata Passent|Agata]], in 1973.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe [[Masurian Lake District]] was among Osiecka's favorite places in Poland. She liked to vacation there in the 1960s/70s with Polish intellectuals and artists. As a student she worked there for one of the local newspapers and in the autumn of her life she wrote for the [[Atelier Theatre]] in [[Sopot]]. She was a frequent visitor to the Halama writers' retreat house in [[Zakopane]], in the Tatra Mountains.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.archiwumagnieszkiosieckiej.pl/dlibra/text?id=about-archive|title=dLibra Digital Library|last=Center|first=PSNC, Poznan Supercomputer and Networking|website=www.archiwumagnieszkiosieckiej.pl|language=en|access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nAgnieszka Osiecka published numerous books and released many records (see the full list at www.okularnicy.org.pl). She is considered one of the most important, prolific and gifted persons in postwar Polish culture and history. Osiecka died on 7 March 1997 after a battle of several years with  colon cancer. She is buried at the [[Pow\u0105zki Cemetery]] in Warsaw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/13541404/agnieszka-osiecka|title=Agnieszka Osiecka (1936-1997) - Find A Grave...|website=www.findagrave.com|access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n\nThe Agnieszka Osiecka Okularnicy Foundation<ref>[http://www.archiwumagnieszkiosieckiej.pl Agnieszka Osiecka Okularnicy Foundation. Homepage.]</ref> was founded by her daughter shortly after the poet's death. The Okularnicy Foundation promotes Osiecka\u2019s work, runs the Poet's Archive, organizes the annual singing competition  \"Let us Remember Agnieszka Osiecka\u201c, manages the Internet archive and publishes books.<ref>Biblioteka Narodowa (2018), [http://www.archiwumagnieszkiosieckiej.pl/dlibra The Digital Archive of Agnieszka Osiecka.] National Library of Poland.</ref>\n\nTo honour her creative output and her work at the National Polish Radio, the Music Studio was named after Osiecka in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.studianagran.com.pl/studia/m1/historia/lang,2 |title=The Agnieszka Osiecka Music Studio |author=Webmania.pl |website=StudiaNagran.com.pl |language=pl |access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of poets]]\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1551092}}\n* {{Discogs artist}}\n* [http://www.archiwumagnieszkiosieckiej.pl The Agnieszka Osiecka Internet Archive]\n* [http://culture.pl/en/artist/agnieszka-osiecka Profile of Agnieszka Osiecka] at Culture.pl\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Osiecka, Agnieszka}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:1997 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Pow\u0105zki Cemetery]]\n[[Category:National Film School in \u0141\u00f3d\u017a alumni]]\n[[Category:Lyricists]]\n[[Category:Polish songwriters]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Romanian descent]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Serbian descent]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Hungarian descent]]\n[[Category:Eastern Romance people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish poets]]\n[[Category:Deaths from colorectal cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Poland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| name = Agnieszka Osiecka\n| image = File:Agnieszka Osiecka Polish writer.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = Agnieszka Osiecka\n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1936|10|09}}\n| birth_place = [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]]\n| death_date = {{Death date|df=yes|1997|03|07}}\n| death_place = Warsaw, Poland\n| resting_place = [[Pow\u0105zki Cemetery]]\n| occupation = Poet, writer, author of theatre and television screenplays, film director and journalist\n| language = [[Polish language|Polish]]\n| nationality = Polish\n| period = \n| genre = \n| subject = \n| movement = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse = [[Wojciech Frykowski]] 1963-1964, Wojciech Jesionka 1966\n| children = [[Agata Passent]]\n| relatives = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = [[Cross_of_Merit_(Poland)|Cross of Merit]] 1979\n}}\n'''Agnieszka Osiecka''' (9 October 1936 \u2013 7 March 1997) was a [[poet]], [[writer]], author of theatre and television screenplays, film director and journalist. She was a prominent Polish songwriter, having authored the lyrics to more than 2000 songs, and is considered an icon of Polish culture.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/womensstudiesenc0001unse/page/1107|title=Women's studies encyclopedia|last=|first=|date=1999|publisher=Greenwood Press|others=Tierney, Helen.|year=|isbn=9780313310720|edition=Rev. and expanded|location=Westport, Conn.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/womensstudiesenc0001unse/page/1107 1107]|oclc=38504469}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nOsiecka was born in [[Warsaw]], the only child of Wiktor Osiecki, a pianist and composer of [[Serbs|Serbian]], [[Romanians|Romanian]]-[[Vlachs|Vlach]] and [[Hungarians|Hungarian]] descent, and a scholar Maria Sztechman. She spent her early years in [[Zakopane]] where her father played the piano at the Watra Restaurant. After World War II the Osiecki family moved to Warsaw and settled in the Saska K\u0119pa borough. The small flat soon became Osiecka\u2019s favourite place to work. She lived there almost her entire life. After her death, the ''Okularnicy'' Foundation placed a commemorative plaque on the building.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://culture.pl/en/artist/agnieszka-osiecka|title=Agnieszka Osiecka {{!}} Artist {{!}} Culture.pl|work=Culture.pl|access-date=2018-03-23|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAgnieszka was exceptionally gifted. She completed her coursework much more quickly than other students and graduated from Marie Curie-Sk\u0142odowska High School in 1952. She trained as a swimmer at Legia Sports Club and studied journalism at the [[University of Warsaw]] (1957\u201361) and film-directing at the prestigious [[National Film School in \u0141\u00f3d\u017a]] (1957\u201361) but dropped film-directing and started writing. Osiecka published essays and articles in the student press during her university years. She joined the famous [[Student Satirical Theatre]] (STS) in 1954 and wrote 166 political and lyrical songs for this company. She used to say \"I am a journalist, that is why some of my songs are reports which rhyme.\" She served on the artistic board of the STS Theatre until it closed in 1972.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Agnieszka Osiecka monument Warsaw 01.jpg|thumb|Agnieszka Osiecka monument in Warsaw]]\n1962 marked her debut on [[Polskie Radio|Polish National Radio]]. Renown Polish actress [[Kalina J\u0119drusik]] sang Osiecka's lyrics to a hit song by Franciszka Leszczy\u0144ska called \"My First Ball\" (''M\u00f3j pierwszy bal''). One year later at the first [[National Festival of Polish Song in Opole]] in 1963 Agnieszka achieved a major success winning the main prize and six other prizes for her lyrics: \"Piosenka o Okularnikach\u201c (music by Jaros\u0142aw Abram), as well as \"Bia\u0142e ma\u0142\u017ce\u0144stwo,\u201c \"Czerwony kapturek,\u201c \"Kochankowie z ulicy Kamiennej,\u201c \"Solo na kontrabasie\u201c and \"Ulice wielkich miast.\u201c<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.archiwumagnieszkiosieckiej.pl/dlibra/text?id=about-archive|title=dLibra Digital Library|last=Center|first=PSNC, Poznan Supercomputer and Networking|website=www.archiwumagnieszkiosieckiej.pl|language=en|access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n\nShe was now recognised as a prominent young poet and the Polish National Radio offered her a job to create and lead a team to broadcast ''The Radio Song Studio''. She also worked on theatre and television productions. Together with composer Adam S\u0142awi\u0144ski she wrote a series called \"Listy \u015bpiewaj\u0105ce\u201c (\"Singing Letters\u201c). Her first major theatre show \"Niech no tylko zakwitn\u0105 jab\u0142onie\u201c (\"Let the Apple-trees Bloom\") was staged at the [[Ateneum Theatre]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|year=1985|title=Theatre in Poland 1984|url=|journal=London Theatre Record|publisher=I. Herbert|volume=5|issue=1-13|pages=s.589|via=}}</ref>\n\nHer lyrics were set to music by such composers as [[Krzysztof Komeda]], [[Seweryn Krajewski]], [[Adam S\u0142awi\u0144ski]], [[Zygmunt Konieczny]], and others.\n\n==Personal life==\nOsiecka and her partner, the prominent journalist [[Daniel Passent]], had their only child, a daughter, [[Agata Passent|Agata]], in 1973.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Masurian Lake District was among Osiecka's favorite places in Poland. She liked to vacation there in the 1960s/70s with Polish intellectuals and artists. As a student she worked there for one of the local newspapers and in the autumn of her life she wrote for the [[Atelier Theatre]] in [[Sopot]]. She was a frequent visitor to the Halama writers' retreat house in Zakopane, in the Tatra Mountains.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.archiwumagnieszkiosieckiej.pl/dlibra/text?id=about-archive|title=dLibra Digital Library|last=Center|first=PSNC, Poznan Supercomputer and Networking|website=www.archiwumagnieszkiosieckiej.pl|language=en|access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nAgnieszka Osiecka published numerous books and released many records (see the full list at www.okularnicy.org.pl). She is considered one of the most important, prolific and gifted persons in postwar Polish culture and history. Osiecka died on 7 March 1997 after a battle of several years with  colon cancer. She is buried at the [[Pow\u0105zki Cemetery]] in Warsaw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/13541404/agnieszka-osiecka|title=Agnieszka Osiecka (1936-1997) - Find A Grave...|website=www.findagrave.com|access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n\nThe Agnieszka Osiecka Okularnicy Foundation<ref>[http://www.archiwumagnieszkiosieckiej.pl Agnieszka Osiecka Okularnicy Foundation. Homepage.]</ref> was founded by her daughter shortly after the poet's death. The Okularnicy Foundation promotes Osiecka\u2019s work, runs the Poet's Archive, organizes the annual singing competition  \"Let us Remember Agnieszka Osiecka\u201c, manages the Internet archive and publishes books.<ref>Biblioteka Narodowa (2018), [http://www.archiwumagnieszkiosieckiej.pl/dlibra The Digital Archive of Agnieszka Osiecka.] National Library of Poland.</ref>\n\nTo honour her creative output and her work at the National Polish Radio, the Music Studio was named after Osiecka in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.studianagran.com.pl/studia/m1/historia/lang,2 |title=The Agnieszka Osiecka Music Studio |author=Webmania.pl |website=StudiaNagran.com.pl |language=pl |access-date=2018-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of poets]]\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1551092}}\n* {{Discogs artist}}\n* [http://www.archiwumagnieszkiosieckiej.pl The Agnieszka Osiecka Internet Archive]\n* [http://culture.pl/en/artist/agnieszka-osiecka Profile of Agnieszka Osiecka] at Culture.pl\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Osiecka, Agnieszka}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:1997 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at Pow\u0105zki Cemetery]]\n[[Category:National Film School in \u0141\u00f3d\u017a alumni]]\n[[Category:Lyricists]]\n[[Category:Polish songwriters]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Romanian descent]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Serbian descent]]\n[[Category:Polish people of Hungarian descent]]\n[[Category:Eastern Romance people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish poets]]\n[[Category:Deaths from colorectal cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Poland]]\n", "name_user": "MTKirk", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agnieszka_Osiecka"}
{"title_page": "Henrique Sereno", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Henrique Sereno\n| image = Sereno-2.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Sereno as a [[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]] player in 2010\n| fullname = Henrique Sereno Fonseca<ref name=Profile>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/sereno/fc-porto/1574-399-18083|title=Sereno|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=Portuguese|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|5|18|df=y}}<ref name=Profile/>\n| birth_place = [[Elvas]], Portugal<ref name=Profile/>\n| height = 1.88 m<ref name=Profile/>\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]]\n| currentclub =\n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 = 1995\u20132004\n| youthclubs1 = Os Elvenses\n| years1 = 2004\u20132005\n| years2 = 2005\u20132010\n| years3 = 2006\n| years4 = 2010\n| years5 = 2010\u20132013\n| years6 = 2011\u20132012\n| years7 = 2012\u20132013\n| years8 = 2013\u20132015\n| years9 = 2015\u20132016\n| years10 = 2016\n| years11 = 2017\n| years12 = 2017\n| clubs1 = [[O Elvas C.A.D.|O Elvas]]\n| clubs2 = [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria Guimar\u00e3es]]\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[F.C. Famalic\u00e3o|Famalic\u00e3o]] (loan)\n| clubs4 = [[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]]\n| clubs5 = [[FC Porto|Porto]]\n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[1. FC K\u00f6ln]] (loan)\n| clubs7 = \u2192 [[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]] (loan)\n| clubs8 = [[Kayserispor]]\n| clubs9 = [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]]\n| clubs10 = [[ATK (football club)|ATK]]\n| clubs11 = [[UD Almer\u00eda|Almer\u00eda]]\n| clubs12 = [[Chennaiyin FC|Chennaiyin]]\n| caps1 = 25\n| caps2 = 54\n| caps3 = 23\n| caps4 = 12\n| caps5 = 7\n| caps6 = 25\n| caps7 = 20\n| caps8 = 41\n| caps9 = 0\n| caps10 = 10\n| caps11 = 1\n| caps12 = 18\n| totalcaps = 236\n| goals1 = 1\n| goals2 = 2\n| goals3 = 0\n| goals4 = 0\n| goals5 = 0\n| goals6 = 0\n| goals7 = 1\n| goals8 = 4\n| goals9 = 0\n| goals10 = 1\n| goals11 = 0\n| goals12 = 1\n| totalgoals = 10\n| nationalyears1 = 2007\n| nationalyears2 = 2013\n| nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal U21]]\n| nationalteam2 = [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalcaps2 = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| club-update =\n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n\n'''Henrique Sereno Fonseca''' (born 18 May 1985), known as '''Sereno''', is a Portuguese former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Guimar\u00e3es===\nBorn in [[Elvas]], [[Alto Alentejo Subregion|Alto Alentejo]], Sereno joined [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria de Guimar\u00e3es]] for [[2005\u201306 Primeira Liga|2005\u201306]] from hometown's [[O Elvas C.A.D.|O Elvas CAD]], and served a loan stint during the latter part of that season at lowly [[F.C. Famalic\u00e3o]].\n\nIn the [[2007\u201308 Primeira Liga|2007\u201308 campaign]] he, alongside Brazilian [[Pedro Geromel]], formed a solid defensive partnership as Vit\u00f3ria came from the [[Segunda Liga|second division]] into a final third [[Primeira Liga]] position. On 9 March 2008 he scored a rare goal, in a 2\u20130 home win against [[Sporting CP]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=670176.html | title = Guimar\u00e3es defeat Sporting to go third | publisher = UEFA | date = 9 March 2008 | accessdate = 28 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nSereno spent the vast majority of [[2008\u201309 Primeira Liga|2008\u201309]] in the sidelines after having undergone surgery to both knees, only appearing in six games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guimaraesdigital.com/noticias/37133/sereno-foi-operado-com-sucesso-aos-dois-joelhos|title=Sereno foi operado com sucesso aos dois joelhos|trans-title=Sereno had successful surgery to both knees|publisher=Guimar\u00e3es Digital|language=pt|date=21 October 2008|accessdate=3 October 2017}}</ref> After beginning the following season again in the starting XI (nine matches, one goal), he eventually terminated his contract and, on 1 February 2010, signed with [[Real Valladolid]] in Spain for five months.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.marca.com/2010/02/01/futbol/equipos/valladolid/1265048513.html | title = El Valladolid ficha al central portugu\u00e9s Henrique Sereno |trans-title=Valladolid sign Portuguese centre-back Henrique Sereno | newspaper = [[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] | language = es | date = 1 February 2010 | accessdate = 28 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nSereno made his debut for his new team on 20 March 2010, playing the entire 2\u20130 away victory over [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.eldiadecordoba.es/deportes/Primera-victoria-Valladolid_0_352464892.html | title = Primera victoria en 2010 del Valladolid |trans-title=First 2010 win for Valladolid | newspaper = El D\u00eda de C\u00f3rdoba | language = es | date = 21 March 2010 | accessdate = 9 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Porto===\nIn late June 2010, after [[2009\u201310 La Liga|Valladolid's relegation]] in [[La Liga]], Sereno returned to his country, signing with [[FC Porto]] on a [[Free transfer (association football)|free transfer]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/fcporto/sereno-fc-porto-porto-valladolid/1168469-1304.html | title = F.C. Porto: Sereno confirmado como refor\u00e7o por quatro \u00e9pocas | trans-title = F.C. Porto: Sereno confirmed for four seasons | publisher = Mais Futebol | language = pt | date = 8 June 2010 | accessdate = 11 October 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140329101034/http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/fcporto/sereno-fc-porto-porto-valladolid/1168469-1304.html | archive-date = 29 March 2014 | url-status = dead }}</ref> On 20 August 2011, deemed surplus to requirements as practically all Portuguese players, he joined German club [[1. FC K\u00f6ln]] on a [[2011\u201312 Bundesliga|season]]-long loan deal.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fc-koeln.de/news/detailansicht/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=3758&cHash=509d1add7410f7681715c5f699a80e2e | title = Henrique Sereno verst\u00e4rkt den FC |trans-title=Henrique Sereno strengthens FC | publisher = FC K\u00f6ln | language = de | date = 20 August 2011 | accessdate = 11 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nSereno made his [[Bundesliga]] debut on 27 August 2011, playing the full 90 minutes in a 4\u20133 away defeat of [[Hamburger SV]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://espnfc.com/uk/en/report/321011/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=5739 | title = Late goals hand Cologne dramatic win | publisher = [[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]] | date = 27 August 2011 | accessdate = 11 October 2012}}</ref> He featured regularly during the campaign, but his team suffered relegation.\n\nSereno returned to Valladolid and Spain's top flight for the [[2012\u201313 La Liga|2012\u201313 season]], still under contract with Porto.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://realvalladolid.elnortedecastilla.es/noticias/2012-08-22/sereno-vuelve-blanquivioleta-201208222250.html | title = Sereno vuelve a ser blanquivioleta | trans-title = Sereno again a ''blanquivioleta'' | newspaper = [[El Norte de Castilla]] | language = es | date = 22 August 2012 | accessdate = 11 October 2012}}</ref> He scored his only goal for the former on 24 February 2013, in the 2\u20131 away win against [[Rayo Vallecano]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.levante-emv.com/deportes/2013/02/24/valladolid-congela-ideas-rayo-vallecano/977067.html|title=El Valladolid congela las ideas del Rayo Vallecano|trans-title=Valladolid freeze Rayo Vallecano's ideas|newspaper=[[Levante-EMV]]|language=es|date=24 February 2013|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Later years===\nIn summer 2013, Sereno joined [[Kayserispor]] from Turkey. He made his [[S\u00fcper Lig]] debut on 15 September, featuring the full 90 minutes in a 1\u20131 draw at [[Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi S.K.|Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi SK]]; he ended [[2013\u201314 S\u00fcper Lig|the campaign]] with 22 matches and three goals, in an eventual relegation as last.\n\nOn 27 July 2015, [[free agent]] Sereno returned to Germany by penning a two-year deal with [[1. FSV Mainz 05]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bundesliga.de/de/liga/news/mainz-verpflichtet-henrique-sereno-1-fsv-mainz-05.jsp | title = Mainz verpflichtet Henrique Sereno |trans-title=Mainz acquire Henrique Sereno | publisher = [[Bundesliga]] | language = de | date = 27 July 2015 | accessdate = 3 August 2016}}</ref> The following 15 June, however, after no competitive appearances, he was released.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.goal.com/de/news/968/transfernews/2016/06/15/24654792/mainz-l\u00f6st-vertrag-mit-henrique-sereno-auf | title = Mainz l\u00f6st Vertrag mit Henrique Sereno auf |trans-title=Mainz cancel Henrique Sereno's contract | publisher = [[Goal (website)|Goal]] | language = de | date = 15 June 2016 | accessdate = 3 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nSereno scored his first goal for his next club, [[ATK (football club)|Atl\u00e9tico de Kolkata]], on 18 December 2016. It proved to be the equaliser as they went on to win [[2016 Indian Super League Final|the final]] of the [[Indian Super League]] on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]], against [[Kerala Blasters FC]].<ref name=ISL>{{cite news | url = http://www.hindustantimes.com/football/atletico-de-kolkata-crowned-isl-2016-champions-after-beating-kerala-blasters-fc/story-9WrkSZzrU73zJnH3LYobQN.html | title = Atletico de Kolkata crowned ISL 2016 champions after beating Kerala Blasters FC | newspaper = [[Hindustan Times]] | first = Dhiman | last = Sarkar | date = 18 December 2016 | accessdate = 20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2017, Sereno signed a six-month contract with [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] side [[UD Almer\u00eda]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.udalmeriasad.com/noticia/el-central-henrique-sereno-se-convierte-en-el-tercer-refuerzo-invernal|title=El central Henrique Sereno se convierte en el tercer refuerzo invernal|trans-title=Stopper Henrique Sereno becomes the third winter signing|publisher=UD Almer\u00eda|language=es|date=31 January 2017|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref> On 15 September he returned to the Indian top tier, joining [[Chennaiyin FC]] for free<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/football/indian-super-league-chennaiyin-fc-sign-mailson-alves-and-henrique-sereno/story-qhq76DkgKs5nfX1PuIrxWO.html|title=Indian Super League: Chennaiyin FC sign Mailson Alves and Henrique Sereno|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=15 September 2017|accessdate=12 October 2017}}</ref> and going on to act as [[Captain (association football)|captain]] for the eventual champions.<ref name=ISL2>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/field/943509/how-john-gregorys-chennaiyin-went-from-isl-champions-to-strugglers-in-the-space-of-two-seasons|title=How John Gregory\u2019s Chennaiyin went from ISL champions to strugglers in the space of two seasons|publisher=[[Scroll.in]]|first=Kaushal|last=Shukla|date=13 November 2019|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nTwo years after announcing his retirement at the age of 34, Sereno became president of [[U.D. Vilafranquense]], with the Portuguese second tier club overcome by severe financial problems.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.publico.pt/2020/03/30/desporto/noticia/henrique-sereno-vai-rombo-dificil-1909943|title=Henrique Sereno: \u201cVai ser um rombo, mas o mais dif\u00edcil est\u00e1 feito\u201d|trans-title=Henrique Sereno: \u201cIt will be a big loss, but the hardest part is done\u201d|newspaper=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]|first=Augusto|last=Bernardino|language=pt|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nSereno made his debut for [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] on 10 June 2013, playing the second half of a 1\u20130 [[Exhibition game|friendly]] win with [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] in Geneva.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/news/020a-0e1411a5fba1-7b161d3051d8-1000--portugal-win-the-day-as-halilovic-enters-fray/ | title = Portugal win the day as Halilovi\u0107 enters fray | publisher = UEFA | first = Elvir | last = Islamovi\u0107 | date = 10 June 2013 | accessdate = 11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 24 June 2016, the Elvas city hall commended Sereno for his sporting achievements.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.radioportalegre.pt/index.php/8-radio/5723-camara-de-elvas-aprova-voto-de-louvor-ao-futebolista-henrique-sereno.html | title = C\u00e2mara de Elvas aprova voto de louvor ao futebolista Henrique Sereno |trans-title=Elvas city hall approves commendation of footballer Henrique Sereno | publisher = R\u00e1dio Portalegre | language = pt | date = 24 June 2016 | accessdate = 3 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[O Elvas C.A.D.|O Elvas]] \n|[[2004\u201305 Terceira Divis\u00e3o|2004\u201305]]<ref name=FJ>{{cite web|url=https://www.foradejogo.net/player.php?player=198505180001&language=2|title=Sereno|publisher=ForaDeJogo|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n|[[Portuguese Third Division]]\n|25||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||25||1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria Guimar\u00e3es]]\n|[[2006\u201307 Liga de Honra|2006\u201307]]<ref name=FJ/>\n|[[Segunda Liga]]\n|12||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||12||0\n|-\n|[[2007\u201308 Primeira Liga|2007\u201308]]<ref name=FJ/>\n|[[Primeira Liga]]\n|27||1||4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||31||1\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 Primeira Liga|2008\u201309]]<ref name=FJ/>\n|Primeira Liga\n|6||0||0||0||0||0||6||0\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 Primeira Liga|2009\u201310]]<ref name=FJ/>\n|Primeira Liga\n|9||1||6||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||15||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!54!!2!!10!!0!!0!!0!!64!!2\n|-\n|[[F.C. Famalic\u00e3o|Famalic\u00e3o]] (loan)\n|[[2005\u201306 Segunda Divis\u00e3o|2005\u201306]]<ref name=FJ/>\n|[[Portuguese Second Division]]\n|23||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||23||0\n|-\n|[[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]] \n|[[2009\u201310 La Liga|2009\u201310]]<ref name=SW>{{Soccerway|henrique-sereno-fonseca/17073}}</ref>\n|[[La Liga]]\n|12||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||12||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[FC Porto|Porto]]\n|[[2010\u201311 Primeira Liga|2010\u201311]]<ref name=SW/>\n|Primeira Liga\n|7||0||6||0||0||0||13||0\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Primeira Liga|2011\u201312]]<ref name=SW/>\n|Primeira Liga\n|0||0||0||0||0||0||0||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!7!!0!!6!!0!!0!!0!!13!!0\n|-\n|[[1. FC K\u00f6ln|K\u00f6ln]] (loan)\n|[[2011\u201312 Bundesliga|2011\u201312]]<ref name=SW/>\n|[[Bundesliga]]\n|25||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||26||0\n|-\n|[[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]] (loan)\n|[[2012\u201313 La Liga|2012\u201313]]<ref name=SW/>\n|La Liga\n|20||1||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||21||1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Kayserispor]] \n|[[2013\u201314 S\u00fcper Lig|2013\u201314]]<ref name=SW/>\n|[[S\u00fcper Lig]]\n|22||3||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||22||3\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 TFF First League|2014\u201315]]<ref name=SW/>\n|[[TFF First League]]\n|19||1||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||20||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!41!!4!!1!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!42!!4\n|-\n|[[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]] \n|[[2015\u201316 Bundesliga|2015\u201316]]<ref name=SW/>\n|Bundesliga\n|0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n|[[ATK (football club)|ATK]]\n|[[2016 Indian Super League season|2016]]<ref name=SW/>\n|[[Indian Super League]]\n|10||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||10||1\n|-\n|[[UD Almer\u00eda|Almer\u00eda]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2016\u201317]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]\n|1||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0\n|-\n|[[Chennaiyin FC|Chennaiyin]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Indian Super League season|2017\u201318]]<ref name=SW/>\n|Indian Super League\n|18||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||18||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!236!!10!!19!!0!!0!!0!!255!!10\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n===International===\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=28252|title=Sereno|publisher=European Football|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\"|[[Portugal national football team|Portugal]]\n|-\n|2013||2||0\n|-\n!Total||2||0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Porto'''\n*[[Primeira Liga]]: [[2010\u201311 Primeira Liga|2010\u201311]]\n*[[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]]: [[2010\u201311 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|2010\u201311]]\n*[[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]]: [[2010 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|2010]], [[2011 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|2011]]\n\n'''Kayserispor'''\n*[[TFF First League]]: [[2014\u201315 TFF First League|2014\u201315]]\n\n'''Atl\u00e9tico Kolkata'''\n*[[Indian Super League]]: [[2016 Indian Super League season|2016]]<ref name=ISL/>\n\n'''Chennaiyin'''\n*[[Indian Super League]]: [[2017\u201318 Indian Super League season|2017\u201318]]<ref name=ISL2/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n*{{BDFutbol|12458}}\n*{{TFF player|1630415}}\n*{{NFT player|52583}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sereno, Henrique}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Elvas]]\n[[Category:Portuguese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:LigaPro players]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Second Division players]]\n[[Category:O Elvas C.A.D. players]]\n[[Category:Vit\u00f3ria S.C. players]]\n[[Category:F.C. Famalic\u00e3o players]]\n[[Category:FC Porto players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Real Valladolid players]]\n[[Category:UD Almer\u00eda players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:1. FC K\u00f6ln players]]\n[[Category:1. FSV Mainz 05 players]]\n[[Category:S\u00fcper Lig players]]\n[[Category:TFF First League players]]\n[[Category:Kayserispor footballers]]\n[[Category:Indian Super League players]]\n[[Category:ATK (football club) players]]\n[[Category:Chennaiyin FC players]]\n[[Category:Portugal under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Portugal international footballers]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Germany]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in India]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Germany]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Henrique Sereno\n| image = Sereno-2.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Sereno as a [[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]] player in 2010\n| fullname = Henrique Sereno Fonseca<ref name=Profile>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/sereno/fc-porto/1574-399-18083|title=Sereno|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=Portuguese|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|5|18|df=y}}<ref name=Profile/>\n| birth_place = [[Elvas]], Portugal<ref name=Profile/>\n| height = {{height|m=1.88}}<ref name=Profile/>\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]]\n| currentclub =\n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 = 1995\u20132004\n| youthclubs1 = Os Elvenses\n| years1 = 2004\u20132005\n| years2 = 2005\u20132010\n| years3 = 2006\n| years4 = 2010\n| years5 = 2010\u20132013\n| years6 = 2011\u20132012\n| years7 = 2012\u20132013\n| years8 = 2013\u20132015\n| years9 = 2015\u20132016\n| years10 = 2016\n| years11 = 2017\n| years12 = 2017\n| clubs1 = [[O Elvas C.A.D.|O Elvas]]\n| clubs2 = [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria Guimar\u00e3es]]\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[F.C. Famalic\u00e3o|Famalic\u00e3o]] (loan)\n| clubs4 = [[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]]\n| clubs5 = [[FC Porto|Porto]]\n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[1. FC K\u00f6ln]] (loan)\n| clubs7 = \u2192 [[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]] (loan)\n| clubs8 = [[Kayserispor]]\n| clubs9 = [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]]\n| clubs10 = [[ATK (football club)|ATK]]\n| clubs11 = [[UD Almer\u00eda|Almer\u00eda]]\n| clubs12 = [[Chennaiyin FC|Chennaiyin]]\n| caps1 = 25\n| caps2 = 54\n| caps3 = 23\n| caps4 = 12\n| caps5 = 7\n| caps6 = 25\n| caps7 = 20\n| caps8 = 41\n| caps9 = 0\n| caps10 = 10\n| caps11 = 1\n| caps12 = 18\n| totalcaps = 236\n| goals1 = 1\n| goals2 = 2\n| goals3 = 0\n| goals4 = 0\n| goals5 = 0\n| goals6 = 0\n| goals7 = 1\n| goals8 = 4\n| goals9 = 0\n| goals10 = 1\n| goals11 = 0\n| goals12 = 1\n| totalgoals = 10\n| nationalyears1 = 2007\n| nationalyears2 = 2013\n| nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal U21]]\n| nationalteam2 = [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalcaps2 = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| club-update =\n| nationalteam-update =\n}}\n\n'''Henrique Sereno Fonseca''' (born 18 May 1985), known as '''Sereno''', is a Portuguese former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Guimar\u00e3es===\nBorn in [[Elvas]], [[Alto Alentejo Subregion|Alto Alentejo]], Sereno joined [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria de Guimar\u00e3es]] for [[2005\u201306 Primeira Liga|2005\u201306]] from hometown's [[O Elvas C.A.D.|O Elvas CAD]], and served a loan stint during the latter part of that season at lowly [[F.C. Famalic\u00e3o]].\n\nIn the [[2007\u201308 Primeira Liga|2007\u201308 campaign]] he, alongside Brazilian [[Pedro Geromel]], formed a solid defensive partnership as Vit\u00f3ria came from the [[Segunda Liga|second division]] into a final third [[Primeira Liga]] position. On 9 March 2008 he scored a rare goal, in a 2\u20130 home win against [[Sporting CP]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=670176.html | title = Guimar\u00e3es defeat Sporting to go third | publisher = UEFA | date = 9 March 2008 | accessdate = 28 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nSereno spent the vast majority of [[2008\u201309 Primeira Liga|2008\u201309]] in the sidelines after having undergone surgery to both knees, only appearing in six games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guimaraesdigital.com/noticias/37133/sereno-foi-operado-com-sucesso-aos-dois-joelhos|title=Sereno foi operado com sucesso aos dois joelhos|trans-title=Sereno had successful surgery to both knees|publisher=Guimar\u00e3es Digital|language=pt|date=21 October 2008|accessdate=3 October 2017}}</ref> After beginning the following season again in the starting XI (nine matches, one goal), he eventually terminated his contract and, on 1 February 2010, signed with [[Real Valladolid]] in Spain for five months.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.marca.com/2010/02/01/futbol/equipos/valladolid/1265048513.html | title = El Valladolid ficha al central portugu\u00e9s Henrique Sereno |trans-title=Valladolid sign Portuguese centre-back Henrique Sereno | newspaper = [[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]] | language = es | date = 1 February 2010 | accessdate = 28 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nSereno made his debut for his new team on 20 March 2010, playing the entire 2\u20130 away victory over [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.eldiadecordoba.es/deportes/Primera-victoria-Valladolid_0_352464892.html | title = Primera victoria en 2010 del Valladolid |trans-title=First 2010 win for Valladolid | newspaper = El D\u00eda de C\u00f3rdoba | language = es | date = 21 March 2010 | accessdate = 9 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Porto===\nIn late June 2010, after [[2009\u201310 La Liga|Valladolid's relegation]] in [[La Liga]], Sereno returned to his country, signing with [[FC Porto]] on a [[Free transfer (association football)|free transfer]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/fcporto/sereno-fc-porto-porto-valladolid/1168469-1304.html | title = F.C. Porto: Sereno confirmado como refor\u00e7o por quatro \u00e9pocas | trans-title = F.C. Porto: Sereno confirmed for four seasons | publisher = Mais Futebol | language = pt | date = 8 June 2010 | accessdate = 11 October 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140329101034/http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/fcporto/sereno-fc-porto-porto-valladolid/1168469-1304.html | archive-date = 29 March 2014 | url-status = dead }}</ref> On 20 August 2011, deemed surplus to requirements as practically all Portuguese players, he joined German club [[1. FC K\u00f6ln]] on a [[2011\u201312 Bundesliga|season]]-long loan deal.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fc-koeln.de/news/detailansicht/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=3758&cHash=509d1add7410f7681715c5f699a80e2e | title = Henrique Sereno verst\u00e4rkt den FC |trans-title=Henrique Sereno strengthens FC | publisher = FC K\u00f6ln | language = de | date = 20 August 2011 | accessdate = 11 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nSereno made his [[Bundesliga]] debut on 27 August 2011, playing the full 90 minutes in a 4\u20133 away defeat of [[Hamburger SV]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://espnfc.com/uk/en/report/321011/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=5739 | title = Late goals hand Cologne dramatic win | publisher = [[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]] | date = 27 August 2011 | accessdate = 11 October 2012}}</ref> He featured regularly during the campaign, but his team suffered relegation.\n\nSereno returned to Valladolid and Spain's top flight for the [[2012\u201313 La Liga|2012\u201313 season]], still under contract with Porto.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://realvalladolid.elnortedecastilla.es/noticias/2012-08-22/sereno-vuelve-blanquivioleta-201208222250.html | title = Sereno vuelve a ser blanquivioleta | trans-title = Sereno again a ''blanquivioleta'' | newspaper = [[El Norte de Castilla]] | language = es | date = 22 August 2012 | accessdate = 11 October 2012}}</ref> He scored his only goal for the former on 24 February 2013, in the 2\u20131 away win against [[Rayo Vallecano]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.levante-emv.com/deportes/2013/02/24/valladolid-congela-ideas-rayo-vallecano/977067.html|title=El Valladolid congela las ideas del Rayo Vallecano|trans-title=Valladolid freeze Rayo Vallecano's ideas|newspaper=[[Levante-EMV]]|language=es|date=24 February 2013|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Later years===\nIn summer 2013, Sereno joined [[Kayserispor]] from Turkey. He made his [[S\u00fcper Lig]] debut on 15 September, featuring the full 90 minutes in a 1\u20131 draw at [[Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi S.K.|Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi SK]]; he ended [[2013\u201314 S\u00fcper Lig|the campaign]] with 22 matches and three goals, in an eventual relegation as last.\n\nOn 27 July 2015, [[free agent]] Sereno returned to Germany by penning a two-year deal with [[1. FSV Mainz 05]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bundesliga.de/de/liga/news/mainz-verpflichtet-henrique-sereno-1-fsv-mainz-05.jsp | title = Mainz verpflichtet Henrique Sereno |trans-title=Mainz acquire Henrique Sereno | publisher = [[Bundesliga]] | language = de | date = 27 July 2015 | accessdate = 3 August 2016}}</ref> The following 15 June, however, after no competitive appearances, he was released.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.goal.com/de/news/968/transfernews/2016/06/15/24654792/mainz-l\u00f6st-vertrag-mit-henrique-sereno-auf | title = Mainz l\u00f6st Vertrag mit Henrique Sereno auf |trans-title=Mainz cancel Henrique Sereno's contract | publisher = [[Goal (website)|Goal]] | language = de | date = 15 June 2016 | accessdate = 3 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nSereno scored his first goal for his next club, [[ATK (football club)|Atl\u00e9tico de Kolkata]], on 18 December 2016. It proved to be the equaliser as they went on to win [[2016 Indian Super League Final|the final]] of the [[Indian Super League]] on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]], against [[Kerala Blasters FC]].<ref name=ISL>{{cite news | url = http://www.hindustantimes.com/football/atletico-de-kolkata-crowned-isl-2016-champions-after-beating-kerala-blasters-fc/story-9WrkSZzrU73zJnH3LYobQN.html | title = Atletico de Kolkata crowned ISL 2016 champions after beating Kerala Blasters FC | newspaper = [[Hindustan Times]] | first = Dhiman | last = Sarkar | date = 18 December 2016 | accessdate = 20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2017, Sereno signed a six-month contract with [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] side [[UD Almer\u00eda]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.udalmeriasad.com/noticia/el-central-henrique-sereno-se-convierte-en-el-tercer-refuerzo-invernal|title=El central Henrique Sereno se convierte en el tercer refuerzo invernal|trans-title=Stopper Henrique Sereno becomes the third winter signing|publisher=UD Almer\u00eda|language=es|date=31 January 2017|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref> On 15 September he returned to the Indian top tier, joining [[Chennaiyin FC]] for free<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/football/indian-super-league-chennaiyin-fc-sign-mailson-alves-and-henrique-sereno/story-qhq76DkgKs5nfX1PuIrxWO.html|title=Indian Super League: Chennaiyin FC sign Mailson Alves and Henrique Sereno|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=15 September 2017|accessdate=12 October 2017}}</ref> and going on to act as [[Captain (association football)|captain]] for the eventual champions.<ref name=ISL2>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/field/943509/how-john-gregorys-chennaiyin-went-from-isl-champions-to-strugglers-in-the-space-of-two-seasons|title=How John Gregory\u2019s Chennaiyin went from ISL champions to strugglers in the space of two seasons|publisher=[[Scroll.in]]|first=Kaushal|last=Shukla|date=13 November 2019|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nTwo years after announcing his retirement at the age of 34, Sereno became president of [[U.D. Vilafranquense]], with the Portuguese second tier club overcome by severe financial problems.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.publico.pt/2020/03/30/desporto/noticia/henrique-sereno-vai-rombo-dificil-1909943|title=Henrique Sereno: \u201cVai ser um rombo, mas o mais dif\u00edcil est\u00e1 feito\u201d|trans-title=Henrique Sereno: \u201cIt will be a big loss, but the hardest part is done\u201d|newspaper=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]|first=Augusto|last=Bernardino|language=pt|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nSereno made his debut for [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] on 10 June 2013, playing the second half of a 1\u20130 [[Exhibition game|friendly]] win with [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] in Geneva.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/news/020a-0e1411a5fba1-7b161d3051d8-1000--portugal-win-the-day-as-halilovic-enters-fray/ | title = Portugal win the day as Halilovi\u0107 enters fray | publisher = UEFA  | first = Elvir | last = Islamovi\u0107 | date = 10 June 2013 | accessdate = 11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 24 June 2016, the Elvas city hall commended Sereno for his sporting achievements.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.radioportalegre.pt/index.php/8-radio/5723-camara-de-elvas-aprova-voto-de-louvor-ao-futebolista-henrique-sereno.html | title = C\u00e2mara de Elvas aprova voto de louvor ao futebolista Henrique Sereno |trans-title=Elvas city hall approves commendation of footballer Henrique Sereno | publisher = R\u00e1dio Portalegre | language = pt | date = 24 June 2016 | accessdate = 3 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[O Elvas C.A.D.|O Elvas]] \n|[[2004\u201305 Terceira Divis\u00e3o|2004\u201305]]<ref name=FJ>{{cite web|url=https://www.foradejogo.net/player.php?player=198505180001&language=2|title=Sereno|publisher=ForaDeJogo|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n|[[Portuguese Third Division]]\n|25||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||25||1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria Guimar\u00e3es]]\n|[[2006\u201307 Liga de Honra|2006\u201307]]<ref name=FJ/>\n|[[Segunda Liga]]\n|12||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||12||0\n|-\n|[[2007\u201308 Primeira Liga|2007\u201308]]<ref name=FJ/>\n|[[Primeira Liga]]\n|27||1||4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||31||1\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 Primeira Liga|2008\u201309]]<ref name=FJ/>\n|Primeira Liga\n|6||0||0||0||0||0||6||0\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 Primeira Liga|2009\u201310]]<ref name=FJ/>\n|Primeira Liga\n|9||1||6||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||15||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!54!!2!!10!!0!!0!!0!!64!!2\n|-\n|[[F.C. Famalic\u00e3o|Famalic\u00e3o]] (loan)\n|[[2005\u201306 Segunda Divis\u00e3o|2005\u201306]]<ref name=FJ/>\n|[[Portuguese Second Division]]\n|23||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||23||0\n|-\n|[[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]] \n|[[2009\u201310 La Liga|2009\u201310]]<ref name=SW>{{Soccerway|henrique-sereno-fonseca/17073}}</ref>\n|[[La Liga]]\n|12||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||12||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[FC Porto|Porto]]\n|[[2010\u201311 Primeira Liga|2010\u201311]]<ref name=SW/>\n|Primeira Liga\n|7||0||6||0||0||0||13||0\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Primeira Liga|2011\u201312]]<ref name=SW/>\n|Primeira Liga\n|0||0||0||0||0||0||0||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!7!!0!!6!!0!!0!!0!!13!!0\n|-\n|[[1. FC K\u00f6ln|K\u00f6ln]] (loan)\n|[[2011\u201312 Bundesliga|2011\u201312]]<ref name=SW/>\n|[[Bundesliga]]\n|25||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||26||0\n|-\n|[[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]] (loan)\n|[[2012\u201313 La Liga|2012\u201313]]<ref name=SW/>\n|La Liga\n|20||1||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||21||1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Kayserispor]] \n|[[2013\u201314 S\u00fcper Lig|2013\u201314]]<ref name=SW/>\n|[[S\u00fcper Lig]]\n|22||3||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||22||3\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 TFF First League|2014\u201315]]