{"title_page": "Artemis Fowl (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 film directed by Kenneth Branagh}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Artemis Fowl\n| image          = Artemis Fowl film poster.png\n| border         = \n| caption        = Release poster with theatrical release date\n| director       = [[Kenneth Branagh]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* Kenneth Branagh\n* Judy Hofflund\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Conor McPherson]]\n* [[Hamish McColl]]\n}}\n| based on      = {{based on| ''[[Artemis Fowl (novel)|Artemis Fowl]]''|[[Eoin Colfer]]}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* Ferdia Shaw\n* Lara McDonnell\n* [[Josh Gad]]\n* Tamara Smart\n* [[Nonso Anozie]]\n* [[Colin Farrell]]\n* [[Judi Dench]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Patrick Doyle]]\n| cinematography = [[Haris Zambarloukos]]\n| editing        = Matthew Tucker\n| released       = \n| production companies =  [[Walt Disney Pictures]]<br/>[[TriBeCa Productions]]\n| distributor    = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures]]\n| country        = United States\n| runtime        = \n| language       = English\n| budget         = $125 million<ref>{{cite news|title= Which Movies Are Most Likely to Bomb in 2020? |url= https://observer.com/2019/12/2020-movie-release-schedule-box-office-bombs-prediction/ |work=[[The New York Observer]] |accessdate=February 1, 2020|first=Brandon|last=Katz|date=December 31, 2019}}</ref>\n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Artemis Fowl''''' was an American [[science fantasy]] [[adventure film]] based on the [[Artemis Fowl (novel)|2001 novel of the same name]] by [[Eoin Colfer]] that was set to be directed by [[Kenneth Branagh]] from a screenplay co-written by [[Conor McPherson]] and [[Hamish McColl]], the film stars Ferdia Shaw, Lara McDonnell, [[Josh Gad]], Tamara Smart, [[Nonso Anozie]], [[Colin Farrell]], and [[Judi Dench]]. But the film was cancelled due to the coronavirus.\n\n==Premise==\nThe plot follows the journey of 12-year-old genius Artemis Fowl, a descendant of a long line of criminal masterminds, as he seeks to find his father, who has mysteriously disappeared.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amp.denofgeek.com/us/movies/artemis-fowl/248819/artemis-fowl-trailer-release-date-news|title=Artemis Fowl Movie: Release Date, Trailer, Cast, Director|website=Den of Geek|first=Kayti|last=Burt|date=May 7, 2019|accessdate=September 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{castlist|\n* Ferdia Shaw as [[Artemis Fowl II]], a 12-year old [[human]] [[criminal mastermind]], with exceptionally high intelligence.\n* Lara McDonnell as [[Holly Short]], an 80-year old [[Fairy (Artemis Fowl)#Elves|elven]] [[Ground Intelligence Officer|reconnaissance officer]] of the Lower Elements Police (LEPrecon).\n* [[Josh Gad]] as [[Mulch Diggums]], a [[Fairy (Artemis Fowl)#Dwarves|dwarf]] formerly employed to [[Artemis Fowl I]], serving as an [[informant]] for the LEP.\n* Tamara Smart as Juliet Butler, Butler's younger sister and prot\u00e9g\u00e9.\n* [[Nonso Anozie]] as Butler, Artemis' trusted servant and bodyguard.\n* [[Colin Farrell]] as Artemis Fowl I, Artemis' absent father and [[criminal mastermind]].\n* [[Judi Dench]] as Commander Root, Holly's [[commanding officer]] in the LEP.\n* [[Hong Chau]] as a fairy.\n* [[Miranda Raison]] as Angeline Fowl, Artemis' mother.\n* [[Nikesh Patel]] as [[Foaly]], the LEPrecon division's technical advisor.\n* [[Joshua McGuire]] as Briar Cudgeon, a power-hungry [[lieutenant]] in the LEP.\n* Chi-Lin Nim as Trouble Kelp, a [[captain]] of the LEP.\n* Jean-Paul Ly as Nguyen\n* Matt Jessup as Budd\n* Michael Abubakar as Burr\n* [[Simone Kirby]] as Mrs. Byrne\n* Sally Messham as Sky Willow\n* Bernardo Santos as a Groomsman\n* [[Adrian Scarborough]] as the Goblin Chief\n* [[Vincenzo Nicoli]] as the Goblin Sergeant\n* [[Conor MacNeill]] as the Goblin Lieutenant\n* [[Laurence Kinlan]] as Beachwood Short, Holly's father and a former member of the LEP.\n* Fabio Cicala as Busker Elf\n* Molly Harris as Chrys \n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nIn 2001, plans were announced for a film adaptation of the series.<ref>{{cite news|title=Author's 'Fowl' play includes sequel, movie|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/doc/408896576.html|newspaper=USA Today|accessdate=5 February 2013|first=Ayesha|last=Court|date=8 August 2002}}</ref> [[Miramax Films]] was named as purchasing the film rights with [[Lawrence Guterman]] signed to direct<ref>{{cite news|title=Miramax Has Rights To Make Movie Of Book Artemis Fowl'|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EbgsAAAAIBAJ&pg=6785,890633|accessdate=5 February 2013|newspaper=Star-News|date=19 February 2003}}</ref> and Jeff Stockwell to write.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bing |first1=Jonathan |title=The ol' 'College Try' |url=https://variety.com/2001/film/columns/the-ol-college-try-bidders-take-a-shot-1117796453/|newspaper=Variety|date=3 April 2001}}</ref> In 2003, Colfer stated that a [[screenplay]] had been finalized and that casting was due to start the same year but expressed skepticism over whether or not this would come to pass.<ref>{{cite news|title=A moment with ... 'Artemis Fowl' author Eoin Colfer  |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/default/article/A-moment-with-Artemis-Fowl-author-Eoin-1114885.php|publisher=Seattle PI|accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref> The film remained in development and was assumed to be in [[development hell]] until 2011, when it was reported that [[Jim Sheridan]] was interested in directing the movie.<ref>{{cite news|title=Irish fantasy role raises Saoirse's elf esteem|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/film-cinema/irish-fantasy-role-raises-saoirses-elf-esteem-2621256.html|newspaper=Irish Independent|accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Artemis Fowl Film Attracts Director Jim Sheridan And Star Saoirse Ronan|url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2011/04/17/artemis-fowl-film-attracts-director-jim-sheridan-and-star-saoirse-ronan/|publisher=Bleeding Cool|accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, [[Walt Disney Pictures]] announced that an ''Artemis Fowl'' film covering the events of the first and second novels of the series would be produced by Disney and [[The Weinstein Company]], with the screenplay by [[Michael Goldenberg]]. [[Robert De Niro]] and [[Jane Rosenthal]] signed onto the project as executive producers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vejvoda|first=Jim|title=Disney, Harvey Weinstein Team for Artemis Fowl Movie Adaptation|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2013/07/29/disney-harvey-weinstein-team-for-artemis-fowl-movie-adapatation|website=IGN}}</ref>\n\nOn September 1, 2015, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that [[Kenneth Branagh]] had been hired to direct the film for Disney, with Irish playwright [[Conor McPherson]] as screenwriter and Judy Hofflund as an executive producer.<ref name=\"FilmDirector\">{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Kenneth Branagh Developing \u2018Artemis Fowl\u2019 Adaptation for Disney|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/kenneth-branagh-and-conor-mcpherson-developing-artemis-fowl-adaptation-for-disney-1201583325/|accessdate=September 3, 2015|work=Variety|date=September 1, 2015}}</ref>  On September 12, 2017, Disney announced that the film adaptation would be released on August 9, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movie/artemis-fowl-2019|title=Artemis Fowl - ComingSoon.net}}</ref> The following month, Disney removed [[Harvey Weinstein]] as the producer of the film and terminated its production partnership with [[The Weinstein Company]] following [[Harvey Weinstein sexual abuse cases|a sexual misconduct scandal involving Weinstein]].<ref name=\"DisneyRemovesWeinstein\">{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/harvey-weinstein-disney-artemis-fowl-1202587666/|title=Disney Removes Harvey Weinstein as Producer on \u2018Artemis Fowl\u2019|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=October 11, 2017|accessdate=October 14, 2017|magazine=Variety}}</ref>\n\nColfer supports the changes from the source material in the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/gaming/artemis-fowl-author-supports-the-changes-in-disneys-movie/ar-BB10DYXB|title=Artemis Fowl author supports the changes in Disney\u2019s movie|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nOn September 18, 2017, it was reported that [[Judi Dench]] was in talks for an unspecified role.<ref name=\"DenchCasting\">{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/judi-dench-artemis-fowl-movie-kenneth-branagh-1202562782/|title=Judi Dench in Talks to Join Kenneth Branagh\u2019s \u2018Artemis Fowl\u2019 Movie Adaptation |last=Kroll|first=Justin|magazine=Variety|date=September 18, 2017|accessdate=September 20, 2017}}</ref> On December 20, 2017, it was announced that Irish newcomer and grandson of [[Robert Shaw (actor)|Robert Shaw]], Ferdia Shaw, had been cast as Artemis Fowl II, alongside Dench as Commander Root, [[Josh Gad]] as Mulch Diggums, Lara McDonnell as Captain Holly Short, and [[Nonso Anozie]] as Butler.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Michelle Lema|title=The Cast for the Upcoming Live-Action Adaptation of Artemis Fowl Has Been Announced|url=https://ohmy.disney.com/news/2017/12/20/artemis-fowl-casting/|publisher=Oh My Disney|accessdate=12 January 2018|date=December 20, 2017}}</ref> [[Colin Farrell]] was revealed as part of the cast as Artemis Fowl I via [[Pick-up (filmmaking)|reshoots]] through the release of the second trailer in March 2020.<ref>[https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/artemis-fowl-trailer-reveals-colin-farrell-casting/ Artemis Fowl Trailer Reveals Colin Farrell Casting]</ref>\n\nAuthor Eoin Colfer will appear as an [[Extra (acting)|extra]]. Describing his one scene, filmed in Northern Ireland, Colfer said: \"I walked across a field with a lot of other people. It wasn\u2019t too taxing \u2013 although I did manage to get it wrong a few times. The only direction they gave was: 'Walk across the field and don\u2019t look at the camera.' I must have looked at the camera about 20 times. I have a new respect for actors.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Alberge|first=Dalya|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/dec/14/eoin-colfer-artemis-fowl-film-die-hard-with-fairies|title=It\u2019s Die Hard with fairies ... and a walk on part for the author in Artemis Fowl film|date=2019-12-14|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-02-20|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nOn March 12, 2018, the rest of the cast was announced (including [[Nikesh Patel]] as Foaly) as principal production commenced. The film was shot at [[Longcross Studios]], and in [[England]], [[Northern Ireland]] and [[Ho Chi Minh City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/artemis-fowl-production-start-disney/|title=Disney's 'Artemis Fowl' Officially Starts Production for Director Kenneth Branagh|first=Dave|last=Trumbore|date=12 March 2018|website=collider.com}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was originally scheduled for release on August 9, 2019 by [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/5/7/18535563/disney-new-star-wars-movie-avatar-mcu-phase-4-release-dates-schedule|title=Disney announces dates for new Star Wars movies, MCU Phase 4, and more|work=Polygon.com|date=May 7, 2019}}</ref> but on May 7, 2019, the film was delayed to May 29, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/disney-bumps-new-mutants-and-artemis-fowl-to-2020/|title=Disney Bumps \u2018New Mutants\u2019 and \u2018Artemis Fowl\u2019 to 2020|first=Jeremy|last=Fuster|website=[[The Wrap]]|date=May 7, 2019|accessdate=July 30, 2019}}</ref> The film was eventually cancelled on April 3, 2020 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], and will never come out in theaters ever.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official|https://movies.disney.com/artemis-fowl}}\n* {{IMDb title|3089630}} \n\n{{Artemis Fowl}}\n{{Kenneth Branagh}}\n{{Disney+ Films}}\n<!--\n[[Category:2020s children's adventure films]]\n[[Category:2020s fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:2020s science fiction adventure films]]-->\n[[Category:American fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction adventure films]]\n[[Category:Artemis Fowl]]\n[[Category:Disney+ original films]]\n[[Category:Films based on children's books]]\n[[Category:Films based on fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on Irish novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on multiple works of a series]]\n[[Category:Films based on young adult literature]]\n[[Category:Films shot in England]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Upcoming films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n[[Category:Films not released in theaters due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2020 film directed by Kenneth Branagh}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Artemis Fowl\n| image          = Artemis Fowl film poster.png\n| border         = \n| caption        = Release poster with theatrical release date\n| director       = [[Kenneth Branagh]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* Kenneth Branagh\n* Judy Hofflund\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Conor McPherson]]\n* [[Hamish McColl]]\n}}\n| based on      = {{based on| ''[[Artemis Fowl (novel)|Artemis Fowl]]''|[[Eoin Colfer]]}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* Ferdia Shaw\n* Lara McDonnell\n* [[Josh Gad]]\n* Tamara Smart\n* [[Nonso Anozie]]\n* [[Colin Farrell]]\n* [[Judi Dench]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Patrick Doyle]]\n| cinematography = [[Haris Zambarloukos]]\n| editing        = Matthew Tucker\n| released       = \n| production companies =  [[Walt Disney Pictures]]<br/>[[TriBeCa Productions]]\n| distributor    = [[Disney+]]\n| country        = United States\n| runtime        = \n| language       = English\n| budget         = $125 million<ref>{{cite news|title= Which Movies Are Most Likely to Bomb in 2020? |url= https://observer.com/2019/12/2020-movie-release-schedule-box-office-bombs-prediction/ |work=[[The New York Observer]] |accessdate=February 1, 2020|first=Brandon|last=Katz|date=December 31, 2019}}</ref>\n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Artemis Fowl''''' is an upcoming American [[science fantasy]] [[adventure film]] based on the [[Artemis Fowl (novel)|2001 novel of the same name]] by [[Eoin Colfer]] that is set to debut on [[Disney+]]. Directed by [[Kenneth Branagh]] from a screenplay co-written by [[Conor McPherson]] and [[Hamish McColl]], the film stars Ferdia Shaw, Lara McDonnell, [[Josh Gad]], Tamara Smart, [[Nonso Anozie]], [[Colin Farrell]], and [[Judi Dench]].\n\n==Premise==\nThe plot follows the journey of 12-year-old genius Artemis Fowl, a descendant of a long line of criminal masterminds, as he seeks to find his father, who has mysteriously disappeared.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amp.denofgeek.com/us/movies/artemis-fowl/248819/artemis-fowl-trailer-release-date-news|title=Artemis Fowl Movie: Release Date, Trailer, Cast, Director|website=Den of Geek|first=Kayti|last=Burt|date=May 7, 2019|accessdate=September 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{castlist|\n* Ferdia Shaw as [[Artemis Fowl II]], a 12-year old [[human]] [[criminal mastermind]], with exceptionally high intelligence.\n* Lara McDonnell as [[Holly Short]], an 80-year old [[Fairy (Artemis Fowl)#Elves|elven]] [[Ground Intelligence Officer|reconnaissance officer]] of the Lower Elements Police (LEPrecon).\n* [[Josh Gad]] as [[Mulch Diggums]], a [[Fairy (Artemis Fowl)#Dwarves|dwarf]] formerly employed to [[Artemis Fowl I]], serving as an [[informant]] for the LEP.\n* Tamara Smart as Juliet Butler, Butler's younger sister and prot\u00e9g\u00e9.\n* [[Nonso Anozie]] as Butler, Artemis' trusted servant and bodyguard.\n* [[Colin Farrell]] as Artemis Fowl I, Artemis' absent father and [[criminal mastermind]].\n* [[Judi Dench]] as Commander Root, Holly's [[commanding officer]] in the LEP.\n* [[Hong Chau]] as a fairy.\n* [[Miranda Raison]] as Angeline Fowl, Artemis' mother.\n* [[Nikesh Patel]] as [[Foaly]], the LEPrecon division's technical advisor.\n* [[Joshua McGuire]] as Briar Cudgeon, a power-hungry [[lieutenant]] in the LEP.\n* Chi-Lin Nim as Trouble Kelp, a [[captain]] of the LEP.\n* Jean-Paul Ly as Nguyen\n* Matt Jessup as Budd\n* Michael Abubakar as Burr\n* [[Simone Kirby]] as Mrs. Byrne\n* Sally Messham as Sky Willow\n* Bernardo Santos as a Groomsman\n* [[Adrian Scarborough]] as the Goblin Chief\n* [[Vincenzo Nicoli]] as the Goblin Sergeant\n* [[Conor MacNeill]] as the Goblin Lieutenant\n* [[Laurence Kinlan]] as Beachwood Short, Holly's father and a former member of the LEP.\n* Fabio Cicala as Busker Elf\n* Molly Harris as Chrys \n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nIn 2001, plans were announced for a film adaptation of the series.<ref>{{cite news|title=Author's 'Fowl' play includes sequel, movie|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/doc/408896576.html|newspaper=USA Today|accessdate=5 February 2013|first=Ayesha|last=Court|date=8 August 2002}}</ref> [[Miramax Films]] was named as purchasing the film rights with [[Lawrence Guterman]] signed to direct<ref>{{cite news|title=Miramax Has Rights To Make Movie Of Book Artemis Fowl'|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EbgsAAAAIBAJ&pg=6785,890633|accessdate=5 February 2013|newspaper=Star-News|date=19 February 2003}}</ref> and Jeff Stockwell to write.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bing |first1=Jonathan |title=The ol' 'College Try' |url=https://variety.com/2001/film/columns/the-ol-college-try-bidders-take-a-shot-1117796453/|newspaper=Variety|date=3 April 2001}}</ref> In 2003, Colfer stated that a [[screenplay]] had been finalized and that casting was due to start the same year but expressed skepticism over whether or not this would come to pass.<ref>{{cite news|title=A moment with ... 'Artemis Fowl' author Eoin Colfer  |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/default/article/A-moment-with-Artemis-Fowl-author-Eoin-1114885.php|publisher=Seattle PI|accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref> The film remained in development and was assumed to be in [[development hell]] until 2011, when it was reported that [[Jim Sheridan]] was interested in directing the movie.<ref>{{cite news|title=Irish fantasy role raises Saoirse's elf esteem|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/film-cinema/irish-fantasy-role-raises-saoirses-elf-esteem-2621256.html|newspaper=Irish Independent|accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Artemis Fowl Film Attracts Director Jim Sheridan And Star Saoirse Ronan|url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2011/04/17/artemis-fowl-film-attracts-director-jim-sheridan-and-star-saoirse-ronan/|publisher=Bleeding Cool|accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, [[Walt Disney Pictures]] announced that an ''Artemis Fowl'' film covering the events of the first and second novels of the series would be produced by Disney and [[The Weinstein Company]], with the screenplay by [[Michael Goldenberg]]. [[Robert De Niro]] and [[Jane Rosenthal]] signed onto the project as executive producers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vejvoda|first=Jim|title=Disney, Harvey Weinstein Team for Artemis Fowl Movie Adaptation|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2013/07/29/disney-harvey-weinstein-team-for-artemis-fowl-movie-adapatation|website=IGN}}</ref>\n\nOn September 1, 2015, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that [[Kenneth Branagh]] had been hired to direct the film for Disney, with Irish playwright [[Conor McPherson]] as screenwriter and Judy Hofflund as an executive producer.<ref name=\"FilmDirector\">{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Kenneth Branagh Developing \u2018Artemis Fowl\u2019 Adaptation for Disney|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/kenneth-branagh-and-conor-mcpherson-developing-artemis-fowl-adaptation-for-disney-1201583325/|accessdate=September 3, 2015|work=Variety|date=September 1, 2015}}</ref>  On September 12, 2017, Disney announced that the film adaptation would be released on August 9, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movie/artemis-fowl-2019|title=Artemis Fowl - ComingSoon.net}}</ref> The following month, Disney removed [[Harvey Weinstein]] as the producer of the film and terminated its production partnership with [[The Weinstein Company]] following [[Harvey Weinstein sexual abuse cases|a sexual misconduct scandal involving Weinstein]].<ref name=\"DisneyRemovesWeinstein\">{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/harvey-weinstein-disney-artemis-fowl-1202587666/|title=Disney Removes Harvey Weinstein as Producer on \u2018Artemis Fowl\u2019|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=October 11, 2017|accessdate=October 14, 2017|magazine=Variety}}</ref>\n\nColfer supports the changes from the source material in the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/entertainment/gaming/artemis-fowl-author-supports-the-changes-in-disneys-movie/ar-BB10DYXB|title=Artemis Fowl author supports the changes in Disney\u2019s movie|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nOn September 18, 2017, it was reported that [[Judi Dench]] was in talks for an unspecified role.<ref name=\"DenchCasting\">{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/judi-dench-artemis-fowl-movie-kenneth-branagh-1202562782/|title=Judi Dench in Talks to Join Kenneth Branagh\u2019s \u2018Artemis Fowl\u2019 Movie Adaptation |last=Kroll|first=Justin|magazine=Variety|date=September 18, 2017|accessdate=September 20, 2017}}</ref> On December 20, 2017, it was announced that Irish newcomer and grandson of [[Robert Shaw (actor)|Robert Shaw]], Ferdia Shaw, had been cast as Artemis Fowl II, alongside Dench as Commander Root, [[Josh Gad]] as Mulch Diggums, Lara McDonnell as Captain Holly Short, and [[Nonso Anozie]] as Butler.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Michelle Lema|title=The Cast for the Upcoming Live-Action Adaptation of Artemis Fowl Has Been Announced|url=https://ohmy.disney.com/news/2017/12/20/artemis-fowl-casting/|publisher=Oh My Disney|accessdate=12 January 2018|date=December 20, 2017}}</ref> [[Colin Farrell]] was revealed as part of the cast as Artemis Fowl I via [[Pick-up (filmmaking)|reshoots]] through the release of the second trailer in March 2020.<ref>[https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/artemis-fowl-trailer-reveals-colin-farrell-casting/ Artemis Fowl Trailer Reveals Colin Farrell Casting]</ref>\n\nAuthor Eoin Colfer will appear as an [[Extra (acting)|extra]]. Describing his one scene, filmed in Northern Ireland, Colfer said: \"I walked across a field with a lot of other people. It wasn\u2019t too taxing \u2013 although I did manage to get it wrong a few times. The only direction they gave was: 'Walk across the field and don\u2019t look at the camera.' I must have looked at the camera about 20 times. I have a new respect for actors.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Alberge|first=Dalya|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/dec/14/eoin-colfer-artemis-fowl-film-die-hard-with-fairies|title=It\u2019s Die Hard with fairies ... and a walk on part for the author in Artemis Fowl film|date=2019-12-14|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-02-20|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nOn March 12, 2018, the rest of the cast was announced (including [[Nikesh Patel]] as Foaly) as principal production commenced. The film was shot at [[Longcross Studios]], and in [[England]], [[Northern Ireland]] and [[Ho Chi Minh City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/artemis-fowl-production-start-disney/|title=Disney's 'Artemis Fowl' Officially Starts Production for Director Kenneth Branagh|first=Dave|last=Trumbore|date=12 March 2018|website=collider.com}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was originally scheduled for release on August 9, 2019 by [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/5/7/18535563/disney-new-star-wars-movie-avatar-mcu-phase-4-release-dates-schedule|title=Disney announces dates for new Star Wars movies, MCU Phase 4, and more|work=Polygon.com|date=May 7, 2019}}</ref> but on May 7, 2019, the film was delayed to May 29, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/disney-bumps-new-mutants-and-artemis-fowl-to-2020/|title=Disney Bumps \u2018New Mutants\u2019 and \u2018Artemis Fowl\u2019 to 2020|first=Jeremy|last=Fuster|website=[[The Wrap]]|date=May 7, 2019|accessdate=July 30, 2019}}</ref> The film's theatrical release was eventually cancelled on April 3, 2020 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], and will instead debut on [[Disney+]] on a currently  undisclosed date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/black-widow-moves-to-november-as-other-mcu-films-shift-back-to-2021-2022/|title=\u2018Black Widow\u2019 Moves to November as Other MCU Films Shift Back to 2021, 2022|website=The Wrap|first=Brian|last=Welk|date=April 3, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official|https://movies.disney.com/artemis-fowl}}\n* {{IMDb title|3089630}} \n\n{{Artemis Fowl}}\n{{Kenneth Branagh}}\n{{Disney+ Films}}\n<!--\n[[Category:2020s children's adventure films]]\n[[Category:2020s fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:2020s science fiction adventure films]]-->\n[[Category:American fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction adventure films]]\n[[Category:Artemis Fowl]]\n[[Category:Disney+ original films]]\n[[Category:Films based on children's books]]\n[[Category:Films based on fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on Irish novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on multiple works of a series]]\n[[Category:Films based on young adult literature]]\n[[Category:Films shot in England]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Upcoming films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n[[Category:Films not released in theaters due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "216.213.7.47", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artemis_Fowl_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Sir Gilbert Heathcote, 1st Baronet", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sir Gilbert Heathcote, 1st Baronet\n| image = \n| alt = \n| office = [[Sheriff of London]]\n| term_start = 1703\n| term_end = 1704\n| office2 = [[Lord Mayor of London]]\n| term_start2 = 1710\n| term_end2 = 1711\n| predecessor2 = [[Sir Samuel Garrard, 4th Baronet]]\n| successor2 = [[Robert Beachcroft|Sir Robert Beachcroft]]\n| office3 = Director of the [[Bank of England]]\n| term_start3 = 1694\n| term_end3 = 1733\n| office4 = President of [[St Thomas' Hospital]]\n| term_start4 = 1722\n| term_end4 = 1733\n| constituency_MP5 = [[City of London (UK Parliament constituency)|City of London]]\n| term_start5 = 1701\n| term_end5 = 1710\n| constituency_MP6 = [[Helston (UK Parliament constituency)|Helston]]\n| term_start6 = 1715\n| term_end6 = 1722\n| constituency_MP7 = [[Lymington (UK Parliament constituency)|Lymington]] \n| term_start7 = 1722\n| term_end7 = 1727\n| constituency_MP8 = [[St Germans (UK Parliament constituency)|St St Germans]] \n| term_start8 = 1727\n| term_end8 = 1733\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1652|1|2}}\n| birth_place = Chesterfield\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|1733|1|25|1652|1|2}}\n| death_place = Lonson\n| father = Gilbert Heathcote \n| mother = Anne Dickons\n| party = [[British Whig Party|Whig]]\n}}\n'''Sir Gilbert Heathcote, 1st Baronet''' (2 January 1652&nbsp;\u2013 25 January 1733) was a British merchant and Whig politician who sat in the [[English House of Commons|English]] and [[House of Commons of Great Britain|British House of Commons]] between 1701 and 1733. He was a [[Governor of the Bank of England]] and was [[Lord Mayor of London]] in 1711. \n\n==Early life==\nHeathcote was the eldest son of Gilbert Heathcote of Chesterfield, Derbyshire, and his wife Anne Dickons, daughter of George Dickons of Chesterfield. He began his apprenticeship as a merchant overseas, and returned to England in 1680 to set himself up as a City trader. He became a Freeman of the [[Worshipful Company of Vintners| Vintners\u2019 Company]] in 1681. On 30 May 1682, he married Hester Rayner, daughter of Christopher Rayner, merchant, of London.<ref name=Cokayne5a>{{Citation| editor-last=Cokayne |editor-first=George Edward |year=1906|title= Complete Baronetage volume 5 (1707\u20131800) - London|url= http://www.archive.org/stream/cu31924092524416#page/n95/mode/2up |volume=5| location=Exeter |publisher=William Pollard and Co| pages=95| accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref> He was living in the parish of St. Dunstan's-in-the-East in 1682 and established a business as a merchant in St Swithin's Lane trading in Spanish wines and other produce.<ref name=DNB>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Heathcote, Gilbert|volume=25}}</ref> He took his first step in Corporation government when elected Common Councilman for Walbrook ward in 1689.<ref name=ALD1>{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/no-series/london-aldermen/hen3-1912/pp119-140 |title=, 'Chronological list of aldermen: 1701-1800', in The Aldermen of the City of London Temp. Henry III - 1912 (London, 1908), pp. 119-140 | author= Alfred P Beaven |publisher= British History Online |accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref> In 1690, he succeeded his father.<ref name=HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/heathcote-gilbert-1652-1733| title= HEATHCOTE, Gilbert (1652-1733), of St. Swithin\u2019s Lane, London; Leyton, Essex, and Normanton, Rutland| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1690-1715)| accessdate = 16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nHeathcote was an agent for Jamaica from 1693 to 1704,<ref name=HOP/> furnishing remittances on behalf of the government for the troops there. He also traded extensively with the East Indies. In 1693 the ship Redbridge, of which he was part owner, was detained by the East India Company, which claimed a monopoly of the trade with India. He asserted at the bar of the House of Commons his right to trade wherever he pleased, unless restrained by Parliament, and the house declared by resolution against the company's monopoly. Heathcote promoted the bill for a new East India Company.<ref name=DNB /> In 1694 he was a Commissioner taking subscriptions to the [[Bank of England]] and selected by ballot as a director of the bank from then, with statutory intervals for the rest of his life. He was a commissioner for Greenwich Hospital in 1695. In 1697 he was a trustee for Exchequer bills and became treasurer of the [[Eastland Company]] until 1699.<ref name=HOP/> At a meeting of this company, held in London about 1698, [[Peter the Great]] was present, and was addressed by Heathcote \u2018in high Dutch\u2019 with reference to the importation of tobacco into his dominions.<ref name=DNB /> In 1698 he was a Commissioner for taking subscriptions to the New [[East India Company]] loan subscribing 10,000l. of its capital himself. He was a member of a committee of seven to arrange matters with the old company and became a Director of the new Company until 1704.<ref name=DNB/> name=HOP/>\n\n==Political career==\n[[File:Heathcote arms.svg|thumb|150px|In 1708, Sir Gilbert Heathcote and his brothers were granted a new set of arms, ''Ermine, three pommes, each charged with a cross or'', which added the ''[[ermine (heraldry)|ermine]]'' field to the ancient Heathcote arms, previously ''[[argent]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Heathcote|first1=Evelyn Dawsonne|title=Account of Some of the Families Bearing the Name of Heathcote which Have Descended Out of the County of Derby |date=1899|publisher=Warren|page=48|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A5_iRZpnlbUC&pg=PA48|accessdate=15 September 2017|language=en}}</ref>]]\nAt the [[1698 English general election]] Heathcote stood for Parliament for the [[City of London (UK Parliament constituency)|City of London]], but was defeated. He became a member of the Russia Company in 1699. In 1700 he was master of the Vintners\u2019 Company. He was returned as [[Member of Parliament]] for City of London at the first general election of 1701 but was expelled on 20 March 1701 for his share in the circulation of some exchequer bills. He was however returned at the second general election of 1701.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/heathcote-gilbert-1652-1733| title= Heathcote, Gilbert (1652-1733), of St. Swithin\u2019s Lane, London; Leyton, Essex, and Normanton, Rutland| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1690-1715)| accessdate = 16 August 2018}}</ref> \n\nHeathcote became an [[alderman]] for Walbrook on 30 June 1702<ref name=ALD1/> and was returned again as MP for London at the [[1702 English general election]]. He was knighted by the Queen on 29 October 1702, when she was dining at banquet at the Guildhall.<ref name=DNB/> He was also a manager of the united trade of the English company trading with the East Indies from 1702 to 1704. He was elected [[Sheriff of London]] on midsummer-day 1703, having been fined in 1698 for declining the office, and served for the year 1703 to 1704.<ref name=HOP /> In 1705 he was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]].<ref>[http://royalsociety.org/uploadedFiles/Royal_Society_Content/about-us/fellowship/Fellows1660-2007.pdf Complete List of Royal Society Fellows 1660-2007] in 2 pdfs, published July 2007, retrieved July 31, 2012.</ref> He was a manager of the united trade again from 1705 to 1709. At the [[1705 English general election]] he was returned again as MP for the City of London. He was a trustee for receiving the loan to the Emperor in 1706.<ref name=HOP/> From 1707 to 1710 he was a Colonel of the Blue Regiment of the city Militia, and was treasurer of the [[Honourable Artillery Company]] (HAC) from 1708 to 1711.<ref name=ALD1/> At the [[1708 British general election]] he was returned again as MP for the City of London. He was governor of the [[Bank of England]] from 1709 to 1711.<ref name=HOP /> By an act of parliament extending the Bank's charter to 1710, Heathcote's gain was said to be 60,000l.<ref name=DNB/> At the [[1710 general election]] he lost his parliamentary seat for the City of London.<ref name=HOP/>\n\nIn 1710, when Heathcote was next in seniority for election as Lord Mayor of London, he was strongly opposed by the court party, who objected to the remonstrance he addressed to the queen, but the court of aldermen finally elected him and he served from 1710 to 1711. He was unpopular and for this reason his Lord Mayor\u2019s procession to Westminster on 30 October was cut short, and the livery companies attended him by water in their barges.<ref name=DNB /> He was the last Lord Mayor to ride on horseback in the Mayoral procession.<ref name=ALD2>>{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/no-series/london-aldermen/hen3-1912/pp195-211 |title= 'Notes on the aldermen, 1701-1838', in The Aldermen of the City of London Temp. Henry III - 1912 (London, 1908), pp. 195-211 | author= Alfred P Beaven |publisher= British History Online |accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref> He was vice-president of the HAC from 1711 to 1720 and resumed his command of the Blue Regiment in 1714 remaining as colonel for the rest of his life.<ref name=ALD1/> \n\nAt the [[1715 British general election]] Heathcote was returned as MP for [[Helston (UK Parliament constituency)|Helston]]. He was appointed [[Commission for Building Fifty New Churches|Commissioner for fifty new churches]] in 1715, remaining until 1727. By 1719 he was Governor of the Eastland Company. He was president of the HAC from 1720 for the rest of his life. At the [[1722 British general election]], he was returned as MP for [[Lymington (UK Parliament constituency)|New Lymington]]. He became president of [[St Thomas' Hospital]] in 1722 for the rest of his life.<ref name = HOP2>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/heathcote-sir-gilbert-1652-1733 | title= Heathcote, Sir Gilbert (1652-1733), of Low Leyton, Essex, and Normanton, Rutland.| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1715-1754 |accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> In 1725 he changed wards and became Alderman for Bridge Without ward, for the rest of his life.<ref name=ALD1/> At the [[1727 British general election]] he was returned as MP for [[St Germans (UK Parliament constituency)|St Germans]].<ref name=HOP2/>He purchased [[Normanton Hall]] in 1729 from [[Sir Thomas Mackworth, 4th Baronet]]. He was appointed a commissioner for the [[Province of Georgia|colony of Georgia]] in October 1732, and obtained much support for the proposal from his fellow-directors of the Bank of England . He was created a [[Heathcote baronets|baronet]] in 1733, eight days before his death.<ref name=Cokayne5a/>\n[[File:Neale(1818) p3.304 - Normanton Park, Rutlandshire.jpg|thumb|Normanton Park, Rutland]]\nAlthough extremely rich, Heathcote's meanness is referred to by [[Alexander Pope|Pope]]; and it was this trait that accounts largely for his unpopularity with the populace.<ref name=DNB/> He died in London on 25 January 1733 and was buried at [[Normanton Hall]], a residence which he had purchased in 1729 from [[Sir Thomas Mackworth, 4th Baronet]]. A monument by the Flemish sculptor [[John Michael Rysbrack|Rysbrack]] is now in [[Edith Weston]] church. [[Caleb Heathcote]] was his brother.\n\n==Descendants==\nA descendant, [[Sir Gilbert John Heathcote, 5th Baronet]] (1795\u20131867), was created [[Baron Aveland]] in 1856; and his son Gilbert Henry, who in 1888 inherited from his mother the barony of Willoughby de Eresby, became [[Gilbert Henry Heathcote-Drummond-Willoughby, 1st Earl of Ancaster|1st Earl of Ancaster]] in 1892.<ref name=\"burkes\">{{cite book|title=Genealogical and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire|date=1914|publisher=Burke's Peerage Limited|pages=96\u201399|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RVggAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA96|accessdate=15 September 2017|language=en}}</ref> \n\n==See also==\n*[[Heathcote (surname)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|en}}\n{{succession box\n | before=[[John Fleet (Lord Mayor)|Sir John Fleet]] | before2=[[William Ashhurst|Sir William Ashurst]] | before3=[[Thomas Papillon]] | before4=[[James Houblon|Sir James Houblon]]\n | title=[[Member of Parliament]] for the [[City of London (UK Parliament constituency)|City of London]]\n | with=[[William Ashhurst|Sir William Ashurst]] | with2=[[Robert Clayton (Lord Mayor)|Sir Robert Clayton]] | with3=[[William Withers|Sir William Withers]]\n | years=1701\n | after=[[William Ashhurst|Sir William Ashurst]] | after2=[[Robert Clayton (Lord Mayor)|Sir Robert Clayton]] | after3=[[William Withers|Sir William Withers]] | after4=[[John Fleet (Lord Mayor)|Sir John Fleet]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n | before=[[William Ashhurst|Sir William Ashurst]] | before2=[[Robert Clayton (Lord Mayor)|Sir Robert Clayton]] | before3=[[William Withers|Sir William Withers]] | before4=[[John Fleet (MP)|Sir John Fleet]]\n | title=[[Member of Parliament]] for the [[City of London (UK Parliament constituency)|City of London]]\n | with=[[William Ashhurst|Sir William Ashurst]] 1701\u20131702, 1705\u20131707 | with2=[[Robert Clayton (Lord Mayor)|Sir Robert Clayton]] 1701\u20131702, 1705\u20131707 | with3=[[Thomas Abney|Sir Thomas Abney]] 1701\u20131702 | with4=[[William Prichard (MP)|Sir William Prichard]] 1702\u20131705 | with5=[[John Fleet (MP)|Sir John Fleet]] 1702\u20131705 | with6=[[Francis Child (1642-1713)|Sir Francis Child]] 1702\u20131705 | with7=[[Samuel Shepheard (died 1719)|Samuel Shepheard]] 1705\u20131707\n | years=1701\u20131707\n | after=''Parliament of Great Britain''\n}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{succession box\n | before=''Parliament of England''\n | title=[[Member of Parliament]] for the [[City of London (UK Parliament constituency)|City of London]]\n | with=[[Robert Clayton (Lord Mayor)|Sir Robert Clayton]] 1707 | with2=[